1. --
{ This informational variation will serve as a handbook/course guide and will explain how to navigate the course effectively. I am well aware that many players will sigh or roll their eyes when they see this 'many'  (and long!)  informational variations, but I have done my absolute best to make sure everything in them is valuable to the reader and helps contribute to the overall value of the course, so I would very much urge you to read them through!  Important variations in the course are marked with bold text to stand out from the rest. In terms of informational variations, these were the ones I deemed necessary to read in order to understand the reasoning behind the opening and play it to its full potential, and in terms of trainable variations, they will be the most commonly played and likely to appear on the board. It is possible to use the option on Chessable to only learn/practice important variations, but I wouldn't recommend this approach, as the course is already very compact and practical.  The first chapter of the course will be dedicated to the aforementioned informational variations and help give you a good glimpse into the decisions made in the course, the philosophy behind it and its purpose. These will aid in your understanding of the opening itself, arm you with play-rates and answer questions you might have  (and probably also a lot more!)   After this, there'll be a multitude of theory chapters, which are all characterized with a corresponding number  (from most to least played)  . Each theory chapter starts with its own roadmap of the opening, containing play-rates and references to the different positions that can arise, as well as an informational introduction to the specific theory chapter. This will aid in your general understanding and help you understand the choices made in the specific chapters.  Apart from the informational variations, the theory chapters will consist purely of trainable variations. In said trainable variations you will encounter helpful arrows and circles with different colors. Here are their meanings:  Yellow arrow/circle = an opponent's idea, threat or piece  Blue arrow/circle = our idea, threat or piece  Red arrow/circle = a prevented idea, often a pin or hanging piece  The course ends with a chapter dedicated to tactics ranging from winning the game to a pawn to getting a slightly better position, some of them mentioned in the theory section of the course and others not. I highly urge players to also finish this chapter, as some of the positions in these tactics arise quite commonly, but weren't worthy of analysis in the theory section of the course - either due to how simple they were, or how I wanted you to find the refutation yourself!  If you have any questions or are just generally confused about something in the course, please do not hesitate to reach out to me! I am more than happy to assist and update/add anything helpful ^^ }
