[Black "Why This Course?"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ @@HeaderStart@@Welcome to the course: 'The Relentless Reti for Casual Players'! @@HeaderEnd@@Let's start by talking about the intention behind the course, so you can make an informed decision about whether this course is meant for you.   When I first created the course, I wanted to make something specifically for casuals  (below 1600 elo)  , but also solid and healthy enough for them to play once they earn hundreds of rating points  (which they will obviously gain from this course, as many of my students already have! :D)  I wanted to create an opening repertoire that dives deeply into the databases and find the best-scoring and optimal variations to play for White at these levels of chess. I didn't want to make yet another super safe, drawish repertoire for White to have to spend hours learning, but instead wanted to arm White with dynamic and explosive chess to have tons of fun, play ambitiously and win many memorable games! The variations in this course are also objectively solid and you won't be worse out of the opening  (not even against strong players!)  , but since it's extremely practical and the variations have been chosen for casuals, the variations chosen don't reflect how stronger players would play with the Black pieces and the course is therefore quite unfit for titled players.  I remembered back to a few years ago, when I was at the level this course is for, where I began learning theory and openings. I learned hundreds, if not thousands, of variations, but barely gained any rating. I drilled variation after variation, only to never see them on the board. Upon switching to an opening more suited for practical play, I gained hundreds of rating points knowing less than 50 variations! I realized I had approached the opening all wrong and as I looked back on what I had learned, none of it was really for casuals. In the many different casual courses I've seen - or even used myself - the majority of them are either:   a. Extremely lacking in variations and explanations  b. Quite dubious or hard to play for a win  c. Based on an opening that is too complicated  d. Have opening choices that don't leave much room to grow  e. Use variations that lower-rated players won't play  f. Prefers solid and mostly boring play  Not only this, but I've also seen countless of repertoires claiming to be for anyone between 800-2400+ elo, which is quite frankly absurd. The perfect opening for a casual is NOT also perfect for a professional rated 2400+. The difference here is not the amount of variations, but the opening choice itself!  (How is your casual opponent supposed to play 25+ moves of theory? If they do, I'll be very impressed!)   Also, if you're going around buying comprehensive and even revolutionary courses made by acclaimed GM's with hundreds upon hundreds of theory variations  (which can be absolute gems of chess and irreplaceable to stronger players)  , as a casual player, one of two things will happen:  1. You will get lost and not learn effectively, if at all! Especially because close to all - if not all - the repertoire choices won't be taking your elo, or your opponent's elo, into account. It might even feel like the course is written in a different language!  2. You will focus almost exclusively on the Quickstarter, which the course isn't designed around, meaning things like gaping holes, difficult variations to understand, opening choices your opponents wouldn't play, and you'll still have to pay for the remaining 90% of the course, that you won't have any use for!  The biggest problem that I had intended to fix completely with this course  (which I believe I have)  was the fact that variations and opening choices were not being tailored to your rating level and not with the intention of helping you navigate the opening more clearly.  With this in mind, I've made commentary in this course specifically for casual players, while still keeping it in chess language and trying to prepare you for potential future courses. I've handpicked all the most played - and sometimes also some lesser-played, but critical - variations from Black. However, I must warn you, that it's quite impossible to make a comprehensive repertoire with this low amount of variations and you'll therefore fairly often find yourself in a position that isn't covered in the course.  The reasoning behind this is quite simple. Memorizing lines and going through hundreds of variations won't make you a better player. Understanding and learning the key ideas and motives in an opening and trying to implement them in your own games in creative and unique ways, THAT is guaranteed to make you stronger!  I've tried my best to only give you examples of the most critical and popular lines, where I will provide deep enough explanations behind the moves there, that you'll be able to come up with similar and logical answers to whatever off-beat try your opponents might play, that isn't already covered in the course.  I hope that you find the selection of variations and explanations satisfactory, if not, please don't hesitate to reach out to me and let me know. I'll gladly take a further look and update the course if necessary, or at least, analyse a bit and share my findings with you!  With all of this being said  (which is a lot, I do realize! :D)  , happy learning and I hope you'll have as much of a blast learning the opening, as I've had exploring and putting it all together. May it serve you well on your path to improvement and keep chess fun and exciting! }
*

