[Black "Philosophy behind The Réti - 1. Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ Welcome to the discussion of the opening itself! Now, I know a lot of people don't exactly squeal of excitement when they see a long informational variation, but I think they're incredibly valuable, so here they are anyway! :D  1. Nf3. This is the move the entire course is based upon.  I imagine many of you will have questions as to why this has been picked and why we don't play some of the more common moves, like e4, d4 or even c4. The answer is actually quite simple, but I'll do my best to go into some more depth, in order to really cement the reasoning behind this choice and prepare you for the rest of the course.  1 - The move 1. Nf3 is the most flexible and non-committal move from White on the first move, period. In almost all variations of both c4, e4 and d4 we develop our knight to the f3 square at some point. It's only in a select few openings where White will go for an early f4, but this isn't necessary at all.  2 - It's very rarely played, especially on the lower levels, and many opponents will find themselves in a sub-optimal, sometimes even down-right bad or losing, position within the first few moves of the game.  3 - We don't commit to any certain pawn structure, meaning we can tailor our pawn-pushes directly to meet everything Black throws at us. Us being able to tailor our pawn pushes means that we can get very dynamic and forcing variations, without our opponents realizing they've been tricked and are in grave danger of getting a significantly worse position.  4 - The setups we adopt are often simple to play, flexible and both objectively sound and practically strong, while also leaving room for you to leave your own creative mark and take the game in the direction you wish.  5 - The far majority of positions that arise from the different structures allow us to play for the exact same ideas, for example, 1. Nf3, 2. c4 and 3. e3 in the 1... d5 chapter, which is played in close to all the variations. This allows us to play very consistently.  These are 5 of the main factors behind choosing The Réti 1. Nf3, as well as the more specific repertoire choices against Black's options, that will be covered in the next informational variations.   For now, I wish you good luck and lots of fun! }
