[Black "Opening Principles"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ I wanted to create this informational variation for players unfamiliar with the general opening principles, or just those who wanted a quick refresher, as these are extremely valuable and will help us navigate the opening successfully.   These not only serve as a solid foundation for all of the variations chosen in this course, but will also help you understand all opening play.  
1. Develop your pieces  In order to get anywhere in a chess game, we have to develop our pieces. It's impossible to make any attacks and try to win a game, if we don't develop our pieces. Not only this, but developing our pieces allows us to grab more space and have more control to navigate, often resulting in a better position. Having more space and control to navigate allows us to attack fast and efficiently to gain advantages.  This is also one of the main reasons why we push pawns in the opening, as we want to open up for our bishops and grab space for our knights.  Generally, we start by developing the knights, then bishops and then we castle. In order to develop our bishops, we obviously also need to push some pawns first.  2. Develop towards the center  We want our pieces in the center, as that's where they'll have the maximum impact. To illustrate this, imagine a knight in the corner of the board. It only has 2 squares to move to, while a knight in the center has 8  (!)  squares. This is a perfect illustration of how much more our pieces can do in the center of the board. Furthermore, a knight in the center can quickly join an attack on either the queen- or kingside, resulting in many more options for attacking, forking, etc.  3. Don't move the same piece twice  This isn't as important as the first two rules, but still a good rule of thumb. We want all of our pieces contributing and making a difference, as simply having a single piece in the center of the board is meaningless, especially if we've spent many moves on it, as our opponent will be able to bully it with his many developed pieces and pawns.  This is also important because of the next opening principle.  4. Castle early  Now, I don't mean extremely early, but as in castle after getting your pieces out, and often even before getting your queenside pieces out. Our king is vulnerable in the center of the board and our rook is better in the center of the board, hence, we generally want to castle as quickly as possible.  
These were the principles I decided to go over, though there's certainly more.  This isn't meant as a thorough explanation of how to play the opening, but more of a simple go-through.  For more in-depth explanations you can always search for information online or purchase a book/course on the subject, a great  (and free!)  Chessable course for you to consider is 'Smithy's Opening Fundamentals', with the link: @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/smithys-opening-fundamentals/course/21302/@@LinkEnd@@ }
*

