{ For this course, I'll be using the Lichess database of people rated 1600 in the time formats blitz and rapid. This means every time I say 'This is the most popular move', 'Most people play', etc., I'm referring to people of this elo on this website. For those interested, this database has more than 28 million games. }
1. Nf3
{ The Réti 1. Nf3 is actually only played in roughly 2.2% of all games at this level, which we hope to use to our advantage.   1...d5  has a roughly 36% play-rate.    1...Nf6  has a roughly 12.5% play-rate.    1...Nc6  has a roughly 11% play-rate    1...c5  has a roughly 10% play-rate    1...e6  has a roughly 9.5% play-rate    1...d6  has a roughly 5% play-rate    1...g6  has a roughly 4% play-rate    1...c6  has a roughly 4% play-rate  Combined, the play-rate for these are over 90%. We also have a chapter dedicated to odds and ends like 1... b6.  I have planned the course accordingly, putting a lot of emphasis on the 1... d5 variations and only giving a small amount of variations against 1... d6 and 1... g6.   1... e6 and 1... c6 also aren't covered independently, due to how the vast majority of games transpose after 2. c4 by White, as there seems to be nothing better for Black than to eventually play d5, b6 or g6.  It can be good to know these play-rates yourself to prioritize what you want to learn in the course!  On top of this, I've also structured the course to have chapters of the most played moves first  (Réti Gambit: Accepted)  and the least played last  (Odds and ends)  , so you'll start by learning the absolutely most played variations and end with the least common! Though, there's no system in place for the individual variations in the different chapters, other than the important variations feature.  Good luck and happy learning! :D }
