[White "Typical Ideas in the Réti"]
[Black "Thematic Play vs b5 Structures"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/p1p1pppp/8/1p6/2p5/4PN2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this informational variation we will be taking a look at thematic play against structure with b5 from Black, with the moves being taken from atheoretical variation from thefirst chapter of the course.  We will also discuss more general ways to approach similar pawn structures in other openings and explain why the moves we play are the right ones given the circumstances. }
1. a4
{ I wasn't sure whether or not to give this move an exclamation point, but it's such an important resource to be aware of against b5 structures!  Even if White had a knight on c3  (which would allow Black to play b4)  White would still have fairly good play after Na2, putting pressure on the Black pawns and tearing down the structure with active play.  In our specific case, we haven't committed any pieces yet  (except for our great knight on f3)  and since Black also hasn't moved any pieces or prepared for b5 in any way, we can look to fully punish Black and get an edge often not available in similar structures in other openings. }
1... c6
{ This seems to be the most logical way for Black to defend their weak pawn on b5, as other moves fall flat for different reasons  (they'll be mentioned in the course)  , for now, we will simply look at this move, as it's the most universally thematic move and also most popular move in this specific instance. }
2. axb5 cxb5
{ In similar positions to this, White would often go for the move b3 to tear down Black's structure  (which also leaves White much better in this position)  , but we have an even stronger move.  The two things to notice about this particular position, is the weak diagonal to Black's rook, hinting at Qf3 in the future, as well as there being no pawns to defend the b5 pawn. Because of this, we can turn up the dial and keep attacking the Black pawns.  It's important to note that these pawns are also a real nuisance if we try to grab space with a move like d4. }
3. Nc3
{ This is a great move in our specific instance! The knight develops and attacks the b5 pawn, and unlike most similar structures, b4? doesn't work due to Qa4+! winning both of Black's pawns.  Combining that with the pin on the rook, there are a few options for Black to hold onto the pawn, which will be analyzed in the course. }
3... Bd7
{ This seems to be the most obvious, as now there's no easy way for White to keep attacking the pawn chain, but we don't need to! }
4. Ne5
{ This is the most common position to arise from the entirety of this course, even though in this position, White already has a decisive advantage and will often obtain a completely winning position in the next few moves.  With the threat of Qf3, threats of capturing on f7, threats of capturing the rook, threats of capturing on b5, threat of playing b3, etc. Black is doomed to an extremely rough defensive task, which can't be done objectively sound. }
