[SetUp "1"]

{ In this informational variation we will be taking a look at thematic play against slow play from Black, with the moves being taken from atheoretical variation from thefirst chapter of the course. }
1. d4
{ While we often stray away from playing d4, as it often transposes into well-known theory, most Black players  (on the casual level)  are unaware of the best moves and will play slow and steady in these positions.  This often resolves in a big advantage for White. In other instances, we simply play d4 to punish Black's slow/poor play and don't mind transposing into d4 territory at all, as it's very beneficial positions for us. }
1... Be7
{ A slow, but solid, move by Black. Thematic and simple play follows. } 2. O-O
{ Never hurts to get the king out of harm's way. } 2... O-O 3. Nc3
{ This is an extremely common setup for us to get throughout the course; a knight on c3 and f3, pawns on d4 and e3 and a bishop on either c4 or d3  (it belongs on d3)  .  In these situations we will often look to react to Black's moves to gain as much space as possible and get the most logical piece setup against Black's ideas, which often includes moves like a4, h3, Bd3 and e4 - depending on the individual position. }
3... a6
{ This is a fairly common way for Black to play when their light-squared bishop is unhappy staring at the pawn on e6, in order to try and play b5 followed by Bb7, grabbing space and activating the bishop.  In these situations, we will often look to respond by either striking appropriately in the center  (based on the specific position)  or grab space on the queenside with a4. }
4. e4
{ In this example we look to simply strike in the center and obtain a good position with a strong center.  We can also meet b5 now with Bd3. }
