[SetUp "1"]

{ In this informational variation we will be taking a look at thematic play against early development of Black's light-squared bishop, with the moves being taken from apuzzle in thepuzzle chapter of the course. }
1. Qb3
{ This is one of two most common ways for us to handle Bg4/Bf5 - especially if it comes early!  In some cases moves like   1.Bxf7?  Kxf7  Ne5+  Also often works to win a pawn after capturing back on g4, but in this instance the knight on c6 keeps the f7 pawn safe from the pretty tactic.  In many other openings the most common ways of handling the early pin or development of the light-squared bishop is either h3 or Be2, but since we move our c-pawn very early  (usually with c4)  , we're very often able to meet the pin with active and strong play after Qb3. }
1... e6
{ In this tactical sequence, Black had no way of defending both the pawn on f7 and b7, so they settle for giving up the b-pawn to keep the king safe. }
2. Qxb7
{ White is now simply up a pawn and with a better position. This shows how simple, quick - and deadly! - the move Qb3 can be in response to early development of Black's light-squared bishop. }
