[Black "Thematic Play with cxd5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p4/2P5/5N2/PP1PPPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this informational variation we will be taking a look at thematic play against Black ignoring our threat of cxd5 by not defending the pawn on d5 with a pawn himself. The moves are taken from atheoretical variation from thesecond chapter of the course. }
1. cxd5
{ This is not exactly very common in other openings - other than the Scandinavian - but it's worth knowing the idea, as it often leads to a much better position for White!  We simply force Black to let us get a tempo either with e4 against Nxd5 or Nc3 against Qxd5.  It's worth noting, that the engine is refusing to let us get this tempo and suggests Black to gambit the pawn for just about no compensation with   2...c6!?  dxc6  Nxc6  As Black will at least have some active pieces to show for the pawn, rather than giving up the entire center. }
1... Qxd5
{ This looks very much so like a Scandinavian, and I imagine just about every 1.e4 player will be screaming what to play on top of their lungs! Interestingly, the engine actually quite likes d4 before the text move, but I'm sure it doesn't make any difference.  Again, worth noting that   1...Nxd5  is well met by  e4!  followed up with ideas of Nc3 and d4, taking the entire center and getting a much better position. }
2. Nc3
{ After Black moves the queen, either to a5 or d8, White will look to play play e4  (not d4, as the knight would be pinned on c3)  and - just like we saw in the previous informational about Bg4/Bf5, we meet those moves with Qb3.  White just has a comfortable edge in these positions. It's also worth noting that the traditional Qd8 seems quite bad in this position, as White will be able to use both the center pawns to grab a lot of space. With Qa5, at least d4 and e4 are stopped for the time being. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Ideas in the Réti"]
[Black "Thematic Play vs d4 and c5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/8/2Pp4/5N2/PP1PPPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this informational variation we will be taking a look at thematic play against structures with d4 and c5 from Black, with the moves being taken from atheoretical variation from thesecond chapter of the course.  We will also discuss more general ways to approach similar pawn structures in other openings and explain why the moves we play are the right ones given the circumstances. }
1. e3
{ The right way to handle far-pushed pawns is almost exclusively to challenge them with a center pawn that hasn't moved yet. This is also somewhat reminiscent of an Alekhine/Benko. }
1... c5
{ With this move, we will start seeing very real parallels to the infamous Benko Gambit, where White has played d5 and c4 against c5, and Black follows with similar moves to what we play now.  Much like what we did against the pawns on b5 and c4 in the first informational variation in this chapter, we will look to undermine the pawn structure and take further control of the center and get active play. }
2. b4
{ A strong pawn sacrifice, which is also seen in the aforementioned Benko Gambit. Similar pawn pushes are very common to undermine space-grabbing structures and get initiative for the cost of material. }
2... dxe3
{ The most critical test against our moves! Black wants to accept our pawn sacrifice, but not before trading off their d4 pawn, as   2...cxb4  exd4  leaves a lot to be desired for Black, who now has to fight very hard for crumbs of equality!  Another interesting sidenote is the variation   2...b6?  Which just fails due to  bxc5  bxc5  Nxd4!  A stunning idea!  cxd4  Qf3!  Yet again, like in the previous variation with b5 and c4, taking advantage of the weak long diagonal. }
3. fxe3
{ We can't allow Black to capture on f2 with check and instead look to build up an impressive center. }
3... cxb4 { Black accepts our pawn and we accept the space. } 4. d4
{ This is a very healthy version of the somewhat  (perhaps some would claim fully)  dubious Benko Gambit, as White didn't have to play a3 straight away and instead grabbed a lot of center control.  White will look to play a3 and either capture with the bishop to stop ideas of e6/e5 by Black or capture with the knight to prepare ideas of c5 and Nc4. White has full compensation for the pawn, perhaps even a little more, and definitely has the more comfortable position to play. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Ideas in the Réti"]
[Black "Thematic Play vs g6 setups"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/ppppppbp/5np1/8/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this informational variation we will be taking a look at thematic play against the structure of g6 and Bg7 from Black, with the moves being taken from atheoretical variation from thethird chapter of the course.  We will also discuss more general ways to approach this opening and why we play what we play. }
1. g3
{ This is the setup that I've opted for in this course. It's not as critical and hard-hitting as the more popular setup with e4  (after Nc3)  , but what it doesn't have in objective strength, it makes up for  (more than makes up for, in my opinion)  in practical - and surprise - value.   Not to mention, it's a lot more straight-forward to play and requires less memorization and fewer variations.  With Black's setup, they are effectively giving up all center control for the time being and simply look to castle kingside before striking in the center. Because of this, the choice of this course is to not only grab a lot of space in the center with d4 and c4, but also mimick Black's fianchettoed bishop, in order to effectively 'one-up' Black and keep the position fairly symmetrical.  While it's objectively strongest to play for Nc3 and an early e4 to grab as much space as possible, this makes the position doubled-edged  (or at the very least, unbalanced)  and is most likely what Black was anticipated/hoping for. }
1... O-O { Black is still waiting and not committing yet. } 2. Bg2
{ We follow through with our plan and ask Black what their plan is. It is possible for Black to deviate from just about all well-known theory and play c6!? followed by d5!, with a very fresh and unique position.  This isn't covered in the actual course, as just about every move White can think of secures slightly better play, including moves like: O-O, Nc3, Qb3, b3, a4 and h3. I personally really like the interesting   2...c6  Nc3  d5  O-O!?  dxc4  e4!?  Which certainly promises fun and interesting play.   In this course, however, we will mostly be looking at the by-far most popular move, that is also most consistent with Black's play so far, which is: }
2... d6
{ The good old d6! This move technically is played to stop White from playing e5 in setups with e4 and d4, which is also why the engine prefers Black to play the very unique c6 and d5 setup.  With this move, Black plays more thematic and common chess, looking for either e5 and c5, often only after playing Nbd7, which White will respond to with e4. }
3. Nc3
{ We simply prepare to castle short and have an abundance of possible moves, which we can tailor to what our opponent plays and what we prefer. There's quite a few variations analyzed from this position in the course, but from now on, it's only a matter of time before Black decides how to strike in the center!  Our position is rock-solid, we have a comfortable edge and we're ready to meet Black's challenge of the center, no matter how they do it! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1 - Réti Gambit Accepted - 1... d5"]
[Black "Roadmap of Chapter"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 dxc4
{ This is the starting point of our analysis in this chapter, played around 33% of the time. }
3. e3
{ All the moves so far will be explained in great detail in the informational variationIntroduction to chapter. }
3... b5
{ This is 'The Overambitious' variation, which is played around 25% of the time in this position.   3...Nf6  Bxc4  This is 'The Conservative' variation, which is played around 20% of the time in this position. This continuation is covered in the4th,5th and6th variation.   3...Nc6  Bxc4  This is 'The Center Play' variation, which is played around 12% of the time in this position. This continuation is covered in the7th and8th variation.   3...Bg4  Bxc4  This is 'The Bishop' variation, which is played around 10% of the time in this position. This continuation is covered in the9th variation. }
4. a4 c6 5. axb5 cxb5 6. Nc3 Bd7
{ 6...Qb6  b3  This continuation is played around 15% of the time and is covered in the2nd and3rd variation. }
