[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1 - Réti Gambit Accepted - 1... d5"]
[Black "Introduction to 1... d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5
{ Welcome to the informational variation surrounding d5!  This is the most popular move by far for Black. As explained in the informational 'Opening Database', the move d5 is played roughly 36% of the time, not even counting transposition. Therefore, you can expect to see this position a lot.  Black claims a stake in the center immediately with a pawn, as most beginners have learnt is correct to do, and specifically this move also makes a lot of sense since it stops White from playing e4 and   1...e5?  Nxe5  just wins a pawn for White.  It's worth noting that this also invites White to play 2. d4, which would transpose to a Queen's Pawn opening with 1. d4, which Black probably knows a lot better than the Réti! }
2. c4
{ The Réti Gambit!  We've shown up to play and create fireworks over the board.  The move c4 is indeed an explosive move  (pun intended!)  , putting pressure on Black's center and already getting them into territory they most likely have never stepped upon.  Most beginners will capture the pawn, often even believing that it's free, but the higher rated opponents will almost exclusively play other - and stronger - moves than dxc4, as capturing will give White very good play.  Luckily for us, your opponents won't be rated high enough to understand why taking a 'free' pawn is wrong and will often fall right into our trap and preparation!  We will be looking at the most popular moves from Black, which means some strong replies will not be covered  (especially if they're only played an extremely low percentage of the time)  . The goal of this course is to be practical, prepare you for real games and punish the most common tries. It's not to have you learn hundreds of variations and dull theory, that will never see the dawn of day.  With this in mind, I hope you will have fun diving into these chapters and I wish you happy learning! May you enjoy the spectacular fireworks of the Réti Gambit and light the board on fire! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1 - Réti Gambit Accepted - 1... d5"]
[Black "Introduction to Chapter"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4
{ All the moves so far have been explained in the 'Introduction to 1... d5' in the introduction chapter.  Introduction to 1... d5 }
2... dxc4
{ Welcome to the first chapter regarding 1... d5, more specifically, the Réti Gambit: Accepted.  The main idea in these variations will be to either simply recapture our pawn and gain a better center with more space, or keep attacking/undermining the c4 pawn until it collapses.  We will play energetically and always fight for the center. }
3. e3
{ This move can be seen as the calm before the storm. We don't overextend our pawn to e4  (which is still good, but creates a weakness)  , but instead simply open up the eyes for our light-squared bishop, which prepares to recapture on c4 with our bishop, also developing it to an active square. We also prepare for a future d4, which will be useful in many variations.  If Black doesn't let us recapture, we will  (as mentioned)  apply pressure to their pawn and its defenders until we gain a better position. This is supported by a 60% winrate in this position.  Enough talking, let's jump straight into the variations! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1 - Réti Gambit Accepted - 1... d5"]
[Black "[1] 1 - The Overambitious 3... b5"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
3... b5
{ Welcome to the absolute main line, heart and soul  (maybe a bit exaggerated)  , of the Réti Gambit: Accepted!  Black doesn't want to simply allow White a good game after 4. Bxc4 and instead tries to hang onto the pawn on c4.  At this point, we start our hunt for the pawns and strike directly at the base of Black's pawn-chain, not allowing them to be a thorn in our side.  These variations with 3... b5 are some of the absolute sweetest to play as White, as we will often gain a winning advantage right out of the opening! This is supported by a 67% winrate from this position! }
4. a4
{ Attacking the b5 pawn to try and remove the defense of Black's c4 pawn!  Objectively, it's hopeless for Black to try and hold onto their pawns now.  This is a very thematic way of playing against overextended pawns, like the ones we see here, and is used in many similar openings.    4...a6  axb5  just wins a pawn for White, as the pawn is pinned.    4...bxa4  Bxc4  just allows great play for White.  This leaves only two moves, where the one we investigate now in the theory chapter  (the other is mentioned in the tactics chapter)  is played over 70% of the time. }
4... c6
{ Black is still only moving their pawns, desperately trying to hold on to their extra pawn, but there are too many weaknesses and White is too developed to simply let it slide.  We have a simple and very strong continuation here. }
5. axb5
{ Our continuation starts with capturing the pawn on b5, as we want to weaken the diagonal to the Black rook. }
5... cxb5 6. Nc3
{ An often missed great move from White! We attack the b5 pawn, yet again, it can't move safely and there are no pawns left to defend it.  Our knights are already leaping into the game and we're the one creating threats at every turn, so it should be clear already, that we're in the driver's seat!  A more common way to play against a pawn structure like this  (it's objectively weaker in this specific scenario)  is the move 6. b3. Normally, this is the way to break down the structure, but since 6... b4 isn't possible here  (look at the variation mentioned right beneath this text)  , 6. Nc3 is even stronger.    6...a6  Nxb5  where the a6 pawn is, again, pinned.    6...b4  Qa4+  where White can then capture the b4 pawn with the queen. }
6... Bd7
{ Since the other moves mentioned didn't make much sense, Black tries desperately to hold on to the pawn by developing their bishop.  This move is played roughly half the time, but White actually has an incredible strong resource here, practically winning on the spot! }
7. Ne5
{ What!?  This might be a very strange looking move, but hear me out.  7. Ne5 is a very, very deadly move preparing 8. Qf3 with a fork on the rook on a8 and a mate on f7!  In fact, Black is left without a single good move!    7...Nc6  is the best try for Black, but still loses to  Nxd7  Qxd7  Nxb5  where White has successfully broken down Black's structure, is winning the pawns and gaining a big advantage. }
7... Nf6
{ This is the most tried move, but just flat out loses on the spot.  Black did, indeed, stop our fork on f7 and a8, but the rook on a8 is still looking quite vulnerable, wouldn't you agree? }
8. Qf3
{ BAM!  Our beautiful sequence and knight manoeuvre have allowed us to pick up the Black rook on a8, or at least, a piece on the c6 square.  Who said The Réti was a slow and boring opening!? Not to mention, this is the MOST likely position to appear on the board!  Note: The probability of this position arising is taken from the lichess database of online Blitz and Rapid games at the 1600 rating level. }
*

