1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
3... b5
{ The most played and ambitious move.  Black doesn't want to simply allow White a good game after 4. Bxc4 and instead tries to hang onto the pawn on c4.  At this point, we start our hunt for the pawns and strike directly at the base of Black's pawn-chain, not allowing them to be a thorn in our side.  These variations with 3... b5 are some of the absolute sweetest to play as White, as we will often gain a winning advantage right out of the opening! This is supported by a 67% winrate from this position! }
4. a4
{ Attacking the b5 pawn to try and remove the defense of Black's c4 pawn!  Objectively, it's hopeless for Black to try and hold onto their pawns now.  This is a very thematic way of playing against overextended pawns, like the ones we see here, and is used in many similar openings.    4...a6  axb5  just wins a pawn for White, as the pawn is pinned.    4...bxa4  Bxc4  just allows great play for White.  This leaves only two moves, where the one we investigate now in the theory chapter  (the other is mentioned in the tactics chapter)  is played over 70% of the time. }
4... c6
{ Black is still only moving their pawns, desperately trying to hold on to their extra pawn, but there are too many weaknesses and White is too developed to simply let it slide.  We have a simple and very strong continuation here. }
5. axb5 { Our continuation starts with capturing the pawn on b5. } 5... cxb5 6.
Nc3
{ An often missed great move from White! We attack the b5 pawn, yet again, it can't move safely and there are no pawns left to defend it.  Our knights are already leaping into the game and we're the one creating threats at every turn, so it should be clear already, that we're in the driver's seat!  A more common way to play against a pawn structure like this  (it's objectively weaker in this specific scenario)  is the move 6. b3. Normally, this is the way to break down the structure, but since 6... b4 isn't possible here  (look at the variation mentioned right beneath this text)  , 6. Nc3 is even stronger.    6...a6  Nxb5  where the a6 pawn is, again, pinned.    6...b4  Qa4+  where White can then capture the b4 pawn with the queen. }
6... Qb6
{ This move is less popular than 6... Bd7, but interestingly enough, quite a bit stronger.  White no longer has smart Ne5 ideas nor the a4 push to break down the Black pawn structure, but we haven't run out of steam just yet!  Here it's important to keep up the aggressive playstyle thematic of the course. }
7. b3
{ A very good move! Getting rid of our isolated b-pawn and preparing to take down Black's pawn-chain, the only thing they have achieved!  Any waiting move is met by 8. bxc4 and White is at least getting the pawn back with better play.    7...b4  Na4  Qd8  Bxc4  White is better in this position, as we've gotten the pawn back and have much better play, with 3 developed pieces to Black's 0. }
7... cxb3
{ A mistake that just lets White get a far superior position.  There weren't any good continuations anyway for Black, but this is definitely one of the worse ones, although played fairly frequently in these positions. }
8. Bxb5+
{ Simply capturing the pawn with check.    8...Nd7  Qxb3  This is just a much better position for White, due to the many developed pieces and Black being very tied down. }
8... Bd7
{ The move that Black plays almost exclusively.  It's important here to remember what the other variations have taught us, and not blindly capture the pawn on b3.  That would be exactly what Black wants us to do, as it would make us miss out on most of our advantage!  Instead we will play a nice move... Perhaps even a beautiful move... You might have already guessed it... }
9. Ne5
{ AGAIN a very strong move!  This knight maneouvre just keeps crushing all of Black's dreams!  We're threatening the same ideas of Qf3, but also a new idea, which seems the most likely for us to play in response to Black's most logical move. }
9... Bxb5 { Temporarily winning a piece. } 10. Qxb3
{ A very nice move! The bishop is pinned to the queen, as the a-pawn is pinned, meaning White has a winning position due to the strong knights.  We will play through a sample line. }
10... e6
{ Stopping us from capturing on f7 and opening up for the dark-squared bishop. }
11. Qxb5+
{ Threatening to capture Black's queen, as the pawn on a7 is pinned, forcing both an exchange of queens and winning the piece back. }
11... Qxb5 12. Nxb5
{ The threat is either 13. Nc7+ or 13. Nf7+, depending on what Black plays, winning one of the rooks with a completely winning position.  That should be enough for the 3... b5 variations.   You are hopefully now ready to blow up  (c4 pun intended)  Black's dubious 3... b5 setup and gain some quick wins and easy rating! }
