[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1 - Réti Gambit Accepted - 1... d5"]
[Black "[4] 1 - The Conservative 3... Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
3... Nf6
{ The second most popular move from Black in this position and perhaps also the most precise.  We've already seen what happens if Black tries to hang onto their pawn, and let's just say, it's not exactly pretty.  In these positions, it's important to remember why we played 3. e3, which was to prepare to recapture the pawn with our bishop and play d4, if allowed. }
4. Bxc4
{ We carry on with our mentioned ideas. White already has a good position, which is supported by a 58% winrate from this position. }
4... e6
{ The most played move, asking White to step into a position reminiscent of a Queen's Gambit Accepted  (pawn-structure wise)  , while also staying flexible. There are very real drawbacks to developing the light-squared bishop first for Black, which we'll look at in later variations  (there's a few tactics with this theme also!) }
5. d4
{ We simply carry on with our plan of expanding in the center, preparing short castling and development of our last pieces.  An important question will be what we should do with our dark-squared bishop. Luckily this is often answered instantly by Black's most played next move, ironically enough! }
5... Bb4+
{ A very unneccesary check, forcing us to develop a piece where we would want it anyway.  It makes more sense for Black to develop his bishop to e7  (the second most popular move)  , which we will cover next.  It's worth noting, that it's also possible for White to block with developing the knight to either c3 or d2, if you wish to not trade bishops, but here I see no reason not to. Our light-squared bishop is surely better than Black's and our dark-squared bishop is surely worse. }
6. Bd2
{ Developing our bishop with tempo on Black's, immediately asking them what the plan was.  There will be no pin on a knight and if Black retreats the bishop, we've simply gotten our bishop out on d2 for free. }
6... Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2
{ Another very viable move would be to recapture with the queen instead, getting the knight to c3 instead and perhaps preparing for a rook on d1.  The reasoning behind picking this move is:  a. Our queen would rather be on c2 than d2 the majority of the time   b. There often won't be pressure along the d-file  (hence getting the rook onto d1 doesn't seem to matter and Qd2 doesn't have much value)   c. We don't want to block the c-file, so we can potentially attack along it with Rc1, doubling on the c-file. }
7... O-O 8. O-O
{ Another possibility would be 8. Rc1, but we take the time to castle and wait for Black's next move.  From this point on, there's a lot of different possibilities for Black, but I'll only cover the most played ones. The positions are quite calm and not very critical. Logical development should be enough to net you, at least, an equal position. If you're interested in other continuations, please don't hesitate to let me know, I'll happily take another look!  Alternatively, this might also be a nice opportunity for you to explore a few variations more deeply in order to further familiarize yourself with some of the ideas. }
8... Nc6
{ The most common idea, but followed quite closely by other moves.  This move, to our delight, simply fails to realize our plans of pressure along the c-file, which means White has a real edge. This is supported by a 67% winrate from this position. }
9. Rc1
{ Increasing the pressure along the c-file, preparing 10. Bb5 after moves like 9... b6 or 9... a5.  White already has a very comfortable edge in this position, but we will analyze a few moves deeper to show examples of this, as it might be hard to see any real advantage. }
9... a6
{ Putting a stop to our Bb5 ideas, perhaps also preparing for some b5 and Bb7 action. }
10. a3
{ We take a moment to stop any Nb4 ideas, which also allows for some Qc2 action later on. }
10... b5 11. Bxe6
{ I initially analyzed the, perhaps, simpler option of Bxb5  (which also secures us an advantage)  , but after analysis with the newly released Stockfish 14 NNUE, I have concluded this move to be superior - and also very simple!  We are now left with the only two center pawns in the game and are prepared to either take the Black knight or capture on f7 intermezzo. }
11... Nxd4
{ This is the move I initially 'feared' and therefore thought 11. Bxb5 to be the simplest.  Not to worry, White will get a logical and real edge in this line. I seemed to overestimate the practical counterplay of Black here! }
12. Bxf7+ { Capturing yet another pawn, to secure an extra pawn! } 12... Rxf7
13. Nxd4
{ After everything is said and done, White is completely winning and has even gotten to trade a few pieces off.   According to the engine, White is roughly +3, and while there's no reason to further analyze this simply winning position, it's nice to note the backwards c-pawn for Black  (though it's currently protected by both the rook and queen)  and how our passive knight on d2 is ready to leap into the position on the c5 square. }
