{ The most played again, which is, like the many other variations where Black tries b5, an inaccuracy. }
11. Bxb5
{ This is the old line. All the text has been left intact ^^  Moving the bishop to d3 instead actually gives slightly better play for White, but this is the most obvious continuation, as White simply gets a pawn and can continue to apply pressure down the c-file.  I made this call, as I personally always preferred a clean pawn as a beginner.    11...axb5  Rxc6  White simply has a better position here with pressure on both the b and c-pawn. }
11... Nxd4
{ Black is trying to be cheeky, capturing a pawn first and not allowing us to capture their knight with our rook. }
12. Nxd4 { The simplest move, yet again  (how do I do it!?) } 12... axb5 13.
Qc2
{ We take a second to play Qc2, threatening to capture both the c- and b-pawn.   We will stop the variation here, as the position is quite simple and White has a very real and comfortable edge. }
