[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1 - Réti Gambit Accepted - 1... d5"]
[Black "[6] 3 - The Conservative 3... Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
3... Nf6
{ The second most popular move from Black in this position and perhaps also the most precise.  We've already seen what happens if Black tries to hang onto their pawn, and let's just say, it's not exactly pretty.  In these positions it's important to remember why we played 3. e3, which was to prepare to recapture the pawn with our bishop and play d4, if allowed. }
4. Bxc4
{ We carry on with our mentioned ideas. White already has a good position, which is supported by a 58% winrate from this position. }
4... e6
{ The most played move, asking White to step into a position reminiscent of a Queen's Gambit Accepted  (pawn-structure wise)  , while also staying flexible. There are very real drawbacks to developing the light-squared bishop first for Black, which we'll look at in later variations.  We don't mind going into this territory, as Black no longer has a d-pawn and very often misplays in these positions. }
5. d4
{ We simply carry on with our plan of expanding in the center, preparing short castling and development of our last pieces.  An important question will be what we should do with our dark-squared bishop. Luckily this is often answered instantly by Black's most played next move, ironically enough! }
5... Be7
{ We've already taken a good hard look at the popular 5... Bb4+, so now it makes sense to analyze the better, but less played, dark-squared bishop move.  Black develops their bishop passively, just preparing to castle and often grabs space with their queen-side pawns. This makes more sense than aimlessly checking with the bishop, as we don't get to develop our pieces freely in this variation. }
6. O-O
{ We simply castle and pass the turn to Black.  There's a lot of small improving moves for White, so it makes sense to first get the king to safety, as we will always want to castle eventually, and only then will we decide what else to do after. }
6... O-O 7. Nc3
{ We develop our knight to its most active square and potentially prepare plans like e4, depending on what Black plays. }
7... a6
{ The most played and logical move.  Black's bishop isn't exactly a monster on e7 and the pawn on e6 is blocking their light-squared bishop.  Black will solve most of their problems by preparing to play b5, getting a tempo on our strong light-squared bishop and making room for their own light-squared bishop on the long diagonal. }
8. e4
{ We commit to the aforementioned plan of e4.  This is also calling Black's 'bluff' and prepares to retreat our light-squared bishop to d3 in case of b5 and potentially go for a king-side attack. }
8... b5 { Black follows through with their plan. } 9. Bd3
{ We move our bishop to the most active square available.  It doesn't make much sense to place our bishop on b3, as it will just be looking into Black's pawn chain.  White has more space, a safer structure and better pieces. }
9... Bb7 10. a3
{ We have stopped any ideas of b4, which would allow Black to expand on the queen-side and boot away our knight from the defense of the e4 pawn, and prepare to play for the center with potential moves like e5, Qc2, Re1 and Bf4, depending on what Black plays. }
