[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1 - Réti Gambit Accepted - 1... d5"]
[Black "[7] 1 - The Center Play 3... Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
3... Nc6
{ The third most popular move by Black.  There's a possibility to get very similar positions after an early Nf6 and e6, but we can also get something unique, as Black can play for e5.  Since the move isn't played much and either often transposes to what we've already covered or leads to a significantly better and easier position for White to play  (though admittedly, I've managed to make most variations in the course end this way.. you're welcome :D)  , we'll only cover a few variations. }
4. Bxc4 { We carry on with our mentioned ideas. } 4... Nf6
{ This is usually the knight move that we see on move 3, but here we see it only after Black has developed their other knight to c6.   We will try as much as possible to follow the variations already covered, as there's quite a big possibility for a transposition, and why would we learn a completely new variation, when we can transpose to one we already know with a nice advantage for us? }
5. d4
{ With the same reasoning as the earlier variations. Black has a difficult time taking control over the center and developing their pieces, which is supported by a 60% winrate from this position.  If you want to check out the previous very similar variations for more information on the upcoming moves, you can find them below.  1 - The Conservative 3.. Nf6
  2 - The Conservative 3.. Nf6 }
5... e6 6. O-O Bd6
{ This is where Black deviates from what we've seen previously.  Now we have both the Black knight on c6 and the bishop on d6 taking control over the e5 square, which will allow Black to play e5 in the future - which wasn't possible in the other variations - and we'll see why that is significant. }
7. Nc3
{ We develop our knight to the same square as always, with the idea of grabbing more space in the center and creating threats with the move e4. }
7... O-O 8. e4
{ We follow through with the same thematic plan.  It's always nice to be able to rely on what we know from previous variations, isn't it?  Also, please note the threat of 9. e5!, winning a piece, which results in the following move being played the far majority of the time. }
8... e5
{ A good move that utilizes the Black pieces and doesn't allow us to transpose into already covered positions.  Since e5 is no longer possible for us, and Black has enough control over e5 to recapture in the event of 9. dxe5, we choose to instead push our center pawn. }
9. d5
{ Grabbing more control in the center, asking the knight on c6 where it wants to go and also limiting the options of Black's light-squared bishop.    9...Nd4  doesn't work due to  Nxd4  exd4  Qxd4  where White is simply better. }
9... Ne7
{ The most ambitious move.   Although the knight might look awkward on e7 for the time being, the center is closed and Black therefore has time to relocate the knight to g6.    9...Na5  Bd3  Wouldn't have been good for Black, as White has a simpler position, can harass the Black knight and grab even more space. }
10. h3
{ We take further control over the light squares and ask Black what they're planning to do with the light-squared bishop, now that we've taken control of e6, f5 and g4.  This also prepares the e3 square for our dark-squared bishop, as the h3 pawn stops any knight moves to harass our bishop. }
10... a6
{ Preparing to play b5 to grab space on the queen-side, get a tempo on our bishop and develop the light-squared bishop to b7. }
11. a4
{ A very nice practical move! Also quite thematic in similar positions and can be used in multiple other openings as well.  We've stopped the most obvious ideas by Black and just have a more straight forward and simple position to play.  We can, for example, follow up with developing our bishop to g5 or e3, get our rooks into the center of the board and very long-term we can potentially even play for f4. }
