[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1 - Réti Gambit Accepted - 1... d5"]
[Black "[8] 2 - The Center Play 3... Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
3... Nc6
{ The third most popular move by Black.  There's a possibility to get very similar positions after an early Nf6 and e6, but we can also get something unique, as Black can play for e5.  Since the move isn't played much and either often transposes to what we've already covered or leads to a significantly better and easier position for White to play  (though admittedly, I've managed to make most variations in the course end this way.. you're welcome :D)  , we'll only cover a few variations. }
4. Bxc4 { We carry on with our mentioned ideas. } 4... e5
{ Black goes for the immediate e5, claiming his stake in the center and trying to prevent us from playing d4.  This is the most stand-alone way to play with the knight on c6, that won't look much like our other variations. }
5. d4
{ We still play d4, grabbing the bull by the horns and not allowing Black to get comfortable!  Against this setup from Black, it's important for us to strive for initiative and active pieces  (which d4 certainly helps with)  , so don't be afraid of being confrontational and tactical! If Black tries to play safe with   5...Nf6  Qb3!  is a killer move to secure a big advantage!   We will see how this greatly benefits us in the next couple of moves. }
5... exd4
{ The most played and logical by far. Why else even play 3... Nc6 and 4... e5?   Black, surely, played 3... Nc6 and 4... e5 to grab control of the center and stop us from playing d4, therefore it only makes sense to follow through with the plan.    5...e4  Nfd2  Nf6  Nc3  Bb4  Qc2  Even if White doesn't quite win the pawn on e4, we still have a much more active position and Black has awkward pieces and an overextended pawn. }
6. exd4
{ Taking with our pawn keeps more pieces on the board and now we have a dynamic position!  We have the only center-pawn left on the board, although isolated, it's also fairly far pushed and can be a thorn in Black's side. We're already ready to castle, abusing the Black king still stuck in the middle of the board and our last pieces have great squares to develop to.  This position is objectively still only slightly better, but it's much more pleasant for White to play and Black very frequently messes up! }
6... Bg4
{ A mistake from Black, played around half the time, just showing how difficult this position is to play for Black.  Black pins our knight and therefore prepares to capture on d4. How do we deal with this? }
7. O-O
{ We simply castle!  Black's king is still in the middle of the board, Black is severely underdeveloped and all of our pieces are ready to jump into the battle.  White already has a comfortably better position at this point, but we'll go a bit further to illustrate some points against the most played moves. }
7... Bxf3
{ The most played move, almost played half the time, perhaps trying to prepare to capture on d4, but that would be a blunder, as the d4 pawn will be poison in all variations!    7...Nxd4??  A terrible blunder from Black, that just instantly loses a piece! This is still played 30% of the time.  Qxd4  Bxf3  Qxd8+  Rxd8  gxf3  White is completely winning. }
8. Qxf3
{ White is threatening mate in 1 on f7, Black has to react to this. To illustrate how good this position is, the winrate is over 76% from this position.    8...Qxd4  This also doesn't work for Black  Qxf7+  Kd8  Qxf8+  Kd7  Qxa8  Where Black is completely busted }
8... Nf6
{ Preventing the checkmate, developing a piece to prepare for castling kingside and get more control of the center. }
9. d5
{ An important move for us to play!  We want to strike before Black gets the chance to get the last piece out and solidify their position. }
9... Ne5
{ The most ambitious and obvious knight move, it might look like this is a fork, but we have a trick up our sleeve! }
10. Qe2
{ Both moving our queen out of harm's way, defending our bishop and pinning the Black knight.  Talk about a multi-purpose move! }
10... Qe7
{ Black unpins his knight and perhaps prepares to castle queen-side. } 11. Bf4
{ We simply add more pressure to the knight and x-ray the pawn on c7. } 11...
Nxc4 12. Qxc4
{ We're only a few moves away from developing all of our pieces to the most active and optimal squares and unleashing a strong attack onto Black's king. Black is already on the cusp of being toasted.  It wouldn't be beneficial to spend more time memorizing different variations from here, on the other hand, it's great practice to learn to spot the best moves in a position like this!  I can wholeheartedly recommend to spend a minute or two looking through a few continuations from here, in order to get a feeling for how you can keep the pressure up and take advantage of being far better developed. }
