[White "1 - Réti Gambit Accepted - 1... d5"]
[Black "[9] 1 - The Early Bishop 3... Bg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
3... Bg4
{ This move seems very logical to newer players, as they usually love pinning pieces, especially the knight with their bishops.   It's played a fair bit of the time, although not too often, and it will very often look very similar to what we have already seen in other variations.    3...Be6  Has also been tried a fair amount of times, although it just gives White good play after  Na3!  where White will already get the pawn back with their bishop  Qd5?  Bxc4  has even happened quite a few times in this variation! }
4. Bxc4 { We carry on with our mentioned ideas. } 4... e6
{ The very standard, logical and principled move in these structures - especially since the light-squared bishop has already been developed.    4...e5  loses on the spot to a similar tactic to what we've seen earlier  Qb3!  White both threatens the b7 and f7 pawn and after Black responds in any way possible, White has too many threats and is completely winning }
5. d4 { Our play is similar to other variations in the chapter. } 5... Nf6
{ Black develops the kingside knight, preparing to castle short and control the e4 square. }
6. O-O Bd6
{ The most ambitious and played move, putting the bishop in the center and finally preparing to castle short. }
7. Nc3
{ We gain control of the e4 square and prepare to push our pawn in a thematic fashion. }
7... O-O 8. e4
{ This is just a great position for White and very similar to the other variations in this chapter, which combined with the rarity and simplicity of this line, has resulted in me not going more into detail from here. }
