[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2 - Réti Gambit Declined - 1... d5"]
[Black "[1] 1 - Réti Gambit Declined -  The Ambitious 2... d4 with 3... c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. e3
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
3... c5
{ The most logical and played move by Black.   Black simply defends the d-pawn with another pawn, and since our knight covers the e5 square, this was the only move to do so.  Hopefully, you can already guess how we respond here! When we see a pawn-chain, what do we do? }
4. b4
{ We undermine it! We attack Black's strong pawns and prepare to sacrifice a pawn, if needed, for rapid development and a strong center.  It's important to not give Black the time to consolidate their strong center and gain a lead, but challenge their setup right away.  Hopefully you're beginning to recognize the idea of pushing - even sacrificing - pawns to strike at the base of the opponents pawn-chain. }
4... b6
{ Not only a mistake, but also the by-far most played move by Black and probably the most logical move to a casual.   The idea is to strengthen the center and create a strong pawn chain, this does, however, leave their light squares weak and allows a brilliant tactical shot from White. Maybe you can already begin to see a similarity to earlier positions?  (Hint: look at the arrow) }
5. bxc5
{ We start with the calm capture on c5, not rushing to execute our idea.  There are alternative moves, but this seems to be the most straight-forward one. }
5... bxc5 6. Nxd4
{ A beautiful sacrifice which takes advantage of the Black setup!  This time, we won't develop the knight to e5  (although certainly possible)  to make a fork  (like in the previous chapter)  , but rather just develop our queen to f3 right away, as there's no way for Black to not lose a piece, which would leave us a pawn up! }
6... cxd4
{ What else? If we get to put the knight back on f3 and play d4, we're simply up a pawn with a monster center. }
7. Qf3
{ A great tactical sequence taking advantage of the light squares and abusing Black's movement of their b, c and d pawns. Hopefully you're beginning to recognize this pattern with Qf3!  Usually Black accepts their fate here and gives up the rook, but there is a way for them to keep the rook with   7...Nc6  Qxc6  Bd7  Qf3  which would just leave White with a very comfortable position and an extra pawn, very similar to our text move. }
7... dxe3
{ Black is simply accepting their fate, what else is there to do?  We could obviously just capture the rook here, but there's no need to allow Black to mess up our pawn structure and get compensation. }
8. fxe3
{ The threat of capturing Black's rook is still there and the only way out is the same as mentioned previously. }
8... Nc6
{ Sacrificing the knight. Quite a few people even miss this and just let us capture the rook! }
9. Qxc6+
{ We say thank you very much!   We're now up a clean pawn and an extra pawn is always nice :D }
9... Bd7 10. Qf3
{ White simply retreats the queen to a nice and safe square and enjoys a position with a great center  (especially after the eventual d4 pawn break)  and an extra pawn.  I would recommend considering playing 11. Be2 and 12. O-O, just to get the king to safety and get your pieces out before you start pushing in the center.  Black's pieces are all tied up, almost sleeping, on the king-side and will take time to develop, so we won't have to worry about them coming to life before ours. }
