[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2 - Réti Gambit Declined - 1... d5"]
[Black "[2] 2 - Réti Gambit Declined -  The Ambitious 2... d4 with 3... c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. e3
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
3... c5
{ The most logical and played move by Black.   Black simply defends the d-pawn with another pawn, and since our knight covers the e5 square, this was the only move to do so.  Hopefully, you can already guess how we respond here! When we see a pawn-chain, what do we do? }
4. b4
{ We undermine it! We attack Black's strong pawns and prepare to sacrifice a pawn, if needed, for rapid development and a strong center.  It's important to not give Black the time to consolidate their strong center and gain a lead, but challenge their setup right away.  Hopefully you're beginning to recognize the idea of pushing - even sacrificing - pawns to strike at the base of the opponents pawn-chain. }
4... dxe3
{ The most solid and simple continuation for Black, not falling for our trap with 4... b6. }
5. fxe3
{ We accept being a pawn down in exchange for a great center and much more space. This is objectively sound, but not only that, it is extremely deadly in practical play.  Remember, we don't play for a solid and drawn position, we want to play for a win! If Black allows us to grab the entire center and develop our pieces actively, we will often get a lot more than a pawn for it! }
5... cxb4
{ Black doesn't want to let us capture on c5, especially since any recapture by them could be met by d4  (we will see this in another variation.)  This also temporarily wins a pawn for Black. }
6. d4
{ We happily accept the center we've been given!  The idea for us is almost exclusively to play 7. a3 to secure more squares for our pieces. }
6... e6
{ The most logical and played move by Black. Simply opening the eyes of his dark-squared bishop, preventing d5 and keeping an eye on the b4 pawn. }
7. a3
{ Now we follow through with our idea. We want to activate our pieces and make our compensation be felt. }
7... bxa3
{ The most straight-forward.   If Black doesn't capture on a3, we can try to delay the capture on b4 until they have moved their dark-squared bishop, as we will then win a tempo by capturing. In the meantime we could play Bd3 and O-O. }
8. Bxa3 { We threaten to capture on f8 and stop Black from castling. } 8...
Bxa3 { Black prevents our idea. } 9. Nxa3
{ We take with our knight in order to prepare to jump straight into c4, once it's possible. }
9... Nf6
{ Black develops their last king-side piece, stopping ideas of e4 and also getting ready to castle. This seems most logical and natural to play. }
10. c5
{ We grab even more space and make room for our knight on the beautiful c4 square. }
10... O-O { Black follows through with their idea. } 11. Nc4
{ For the price of a pawn we have much more space on the queen-side, our knights are ready to jump into juicy squares, even threatening to win the rook on a8 already, with all of our pawns contributing, while we also have space for our bishop and queen to utilize the light-squares.  This position is still objectively equal, but we have the practically easiest position to play by far, and I would expect to gain many winning positions from here - even at my level and above. }
