{ Black doesn't want to let us capture on c5, especially since any recapture by them could be met by d4  (we will see this in another variation.)  This also temporarily wins a pawn for Black. }
6. d4
{ We happily accept the center we've been given!  The idea for us is almost exclusively to play 7. a3 to secure more squares for our pieces. }
6... Nf6
{ Slightly different than 6... e6, though this can transpose if played correctly by Black. }
7. a3
{ Now after 7... e6 from Black we transpose to our other variation.  2 - Réti Gambit Declined -  The Ambitious 2.. d4 }
7... bxa3 { This is an inaccuracy and we'll see why very shortly. } 8. Bxa3
{ Very important to capture with the bishop! We only want to capture with the knight and jump to c4 once/if our bishops are traded off. }
8... e6
{ A try to get back into the same territory as the other variation, but this doesn't work here.    8...g6  Bd3  Bh6  Qe2  This seems like the best try for Black, but it doesn't look too threatening for White either. Just keep developing, grab space and try to get the best out of all your pieces. There's plenty of practical compensation and I doubt anyone will find this precise continuation. }
9. Bxf8 { Stopping Black from castling king-side! } 9... Kxf8
{ At least getting the king out of the center, perhaps preparing to play 10... g6 making room for the king on the g7 square. }
10. Nc3
{ Originally I had given 10. Bd3 as the best move, but have since changed my mind, especially after seeing quite a few fails when people went back to review. Note how we don't need c5 or the knight on c4 here! That was only our plan when our knight had to capture on a3, but here we can simply develop it directly towards the center.  This setup is a very ambitious one, now that Black doesn't have an active dark-squared bishop, we can play Nc3, Be2, e4! and castle short. The bishop on e2 leaves both our knight on f3 and our queen protecting the d4 pawn and the knight on c3 prepares to play e4.  We have an extremely ambitious and harmonious setup, with a very real advantage. }
