[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2 - Réti Gambit Declined - 1... d5"]
[Black "[4] 4 - Réti Gambit Declined -  The Ambitious 2... d4 with 3... c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. e3
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
3... c5
{ The most logical and played move by Black.   Black simply defends the d-pawn with another pawn, and since our knight covers the e5 square, this was the only move to do so.  Hopefully, you can already guess how we respond here! When we see a pawn-chain, what do we do? }
4. b4
{ We undermine it! We attack Black's strong pawns and prepare to sacrifice a pawn, if needed, for rapid development and a strong center.  It's important to not give Black the time to consolidate their strong center and gain a lead, but challenge their setup right away.  Hopefully you're beginning to recognize the idea of pushing - even sacrificing - pawns to strike at the base of the opponents pawn-chain. }
4... e6
{ An interesting try for Black, not allowing us to get a huge lead in development, but instead preparing to get their bishop into the game.  In these variations we're not giving up a pawn, but instead choose to force the issue and get into a slightly better endgame  (which is a much better endgame, if Black isn't precise) }
5. bxc5 { We force the issue at hand. } 5... Bxc5 6. exd4
{ This move keeps everything concrete, and we also utilize that the only real option for Black is to give up their dark-squared bishop - losing the bishop pair and leaving the dark squares permanently weak. }
6... Bxd4 7. Nxd4 Qxd4 8. Nc3
{ We have to respond to our hanging rook on a1, but we can do this by developing our knight and we now prepare a cheeky idea, which we will see after Black's next move. }
8... Nf6
{ This seems the most natural, but actually it's better to have the knight on e7, which we'll see after our cheeky move. }
9. Ba3
{ This is the move I was talking about!  We un-pin our knight by developing our dark-squared bishop, which is also preventing our opponent from castling and getting our bishop on a long, uncontested diagonal.  This is usually our idea in these lines, even if Black hadn't played exactly what we've seen so far. }
9... Ne4
{ The only move that doesn't just let White have a significantly better game, though not super intuitive, as it doesn't win material and Black's queenside is still currently sleeping.  REMEMBER TO NOT HANG MATE ON F2! Very important! ^^ }
10. Nxe4
{ We again force the issue at hand and trade down to a simpler and better position for us. }
10... Qxe4+ 11. Qe2 Qxe2+
{ There were no good squares for the Black queen's retreat, not to mention, it's also almost always a good idea to get into an endgame when you're unable to castle. }
12. Bxe2 { We accept our small lead and take the slightly superior position. }
12... Nc6 13. O-O
{ We just have a slightly better position. Pieces are better developed, we have the bishop pair and our king is castled.  Black's light-squared bishop has issues developing to an active square, not to mention, that we can turn up the heat with moves like Rab1, Bd6 and c5, threatening the pawn on b7 if the Black bishop was ever to leave, and our light-squared bishop can either go to f3 or d3 to enjoy nice and long diagonals.  While this position is only slightly better for White objectively, I would say that playing Black in these positions is extremely hard for a human - especially a casual player - and I'd expect great positions for White. }
