[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2 - Réti Gambit Declined - 1... d5"]
[Black "[5] 5 - Réti Gambit Declined - The Ambitious 2... d4 with 3... dxe3"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. e3
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
3... dxe3
{ Black chooses to release the tension in the center, saying they don't want to spend time defending the pawn and would rather focus on piece development.  We don't mind this approach at all, as it more or less ensures that we get a great center and Black is unable to create strong enough threats to gain counterplay for the space we're given. Objectively, and practically, this is therefore an inaccuracy. }
4. fxe3 { The only decent recapture, preparing for 5. d4. } 4... Bg4
{ This is the most played move by Black, but not necessarily the best. It's an objective inaccuracy, in fact.  It's common amongst casual players to develop the bishop to a square where it pins a knight to the opponents queen, but this can be met in numerous ways and is often - in this opening - a slight inaccuracy or even a mistake.  The better, but less common, tries like 4... Nc6, 4... Nf6 and 4... e6 also fail to impress, are all well-met with 5. d4 and 6. Nc3, and will even fairly often transpose, for example:   4...Nf6  d4  Bg4  Be2  e6  and we're back! }
5. d4
{ We simply take over the center.  It's not possible for Black to exploit the pin on our knight, so they'll have to focus on developing the rest of their pieces instead. }
5... e6
{ The most obvious, although slightly passive, move that opens up for Black's other bishop and therefore helps to prepare castling for Black. }
6. Be2
{ We simply break the pin of our knight while developing the last piece between our king and rook. This seems simpler than allowing a pin on b4. }
6... Nf6
{ Black develops a kingside piece, also trying to castle in the near future, while gaining a bit of control in the center. }
7. O-O
{ We simply castle, getting our rook on the nice semi-open f-file and now we're prepared to develop our last pieces. }
7... Be7
{ Black also prepares to castle, most other moves won't change what we play either way. }
8. Nc3
{ We're getting further control of the e4 square, where we want to push our pawn  (this was prevented by Black when they developed the knight to f6.)   Black has also already spent a tempo developing their bishop to e7 and there's no longer a pin if they play Bb4, as our king is castled, so there's no pin to irritate us. }
8... O-O 9. e4
{ We grab even further control of the center and open up the eyes of our dark-squared bishop.   White has a very harmonious position with great space, better pieces, no weaknesses and many options, so we won't dive deeper into this position.  In fact, the engine says the most promising for Black is to give up a pawn with 9... e5 and trade into a worse endgame! }
