[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. e3
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
3... dxe3
{ Black chooses to release the tension in the center, saying they don't want to spend time defending the pawn and would rather focus on piece development.  We don't mind this approach at all, as it more or less ensures that we get a great center and Black is unable to create strong enough threats to gain counterplay for the space we're given. Objectively, and practically, this is therefore an inaccuracy. }
4. fxe3 { The only decent recapture, preparing for 5. d4. } 4... Bg4
{ This is the most played move by Black, but not necessarily the best. It's an objective inaccuracy, in fact.  It's common amongst casual players to develop the bishop to a square where it pins a knight to the opponents queen, but this can be met in numerous ways and is often - in this opening - a slight inaccuracy or even a mistake. }
5. d4
{ We simply take over the center.  It's not possible for Black to exploit the pin on our knight, so they'll have to focus on developing the rest of their pieces instead. }
5... e5
{ The most concrete move available to Black, and it looks interesting, as it threatens to play 6... e4, which would win a piece due to the pin.  It might look a bit scary, but we can simply break the pin and keep developing. }
6. Be2
{ Developing our bishop while unpinning our knight. We're now also preparing to castle and get our rook to the nice semi-open f-file.    6...e4  Nfd2  is just good for White, where Black will struggle to defend the overextended pawn after Nc3 and Qc2 from White, or at least, weaken their position a lot with f5. }
6... exd4
{ Since our knight isn't pinned and 6... e4 didn't lead to anything, Black chooses to release the tension and capture on d4.    6...Bb4+  Nc3  This will often transpose to the text move or at least be very similar. }
7. exd4
{ We capture with our e-pawn to keep a strong center duo of pawns.  White has no apparent weaknesses and we're just able to develop our pieces nicely, enjoy a lot more space and potentially attack down the f-file. }
7... Bb4+
{ Black tries to bother White and also starts developing their kingside. } 8.
Nc3
{ White simply has a significant edge in this position.  We are prepared to castle kingside, perhaps play h3 or a3 and develop our dark-squared bishop to e3 or f4.  There's also a nasty queen check lurking, if Black doesn't do anything to stop it.    8...Nf6  Qa4+!  Nc6  d5  White is going to win a piece and is completely winning. This is a thematic check, that we will see multiple times throughout the course, so keep it in mind! }
