[White "2 - Réti Gambit Declined - 1... d5"]
[Black "[7] 7 - Réti Gambit Declined -  The Ambitious 2... d4 with 3... d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. e3
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
3... d3
{ This is a very odd move that doesn't work for many reasons, which should be apparent given how isolated and lonely it is on d3!  White has numerous strong moves and will just gain a significant lead as a result of this move. I've opted for the most obvious choice and the one that punishes Black's most played - and most obvious - response.  Since this is not played very frequently we will only look at one variation, but its ideas should cover the far majority of games that could occur in this line. }
4. Ne5
{ Yet again we see this Ne5, though in a vastly different position and with different plans  (though the queen is still coming to f3, so not too different plans.)  Simply adding another attacker to the d3 pawn, threatening to capture the pawn on our next move. }
4... Bf5
{ The most obvious and most played move by Black.   Black develops his light-squared bishop to an active square and adds a defender to their, perhaps  (quite)  a bit, overextended d3 pawn... How can this be wrong? }
5. Qf3
{ This is how! We're forking the bishop on f5, pawn on b7, while moving the bishop back to c8 will hang mate on f7.  White is already completely winning at this point, but we'll look a bit deeper, just to make sure! :D }
5... e6
{ The most played move for Black, but our follow-up will be the same against other 'logical' moves like 5... Bg6 and 5... Nh6.  Perhaps better for Black was the following   5...Qc8  Nxf7  Kxf7  Bxd3  with g4 coming on the next move White is, of course, still completely winning. }
6. Qxb7
{ Capturing the pawn and threatening the rook. There's only one way to defend for Black. }
6... Nd7 7. Nxd7 Kxd7
{ Of course not   7...Qxd7??  Qxa8+  Where Black can safely resign. } 8. e4
{ With Black's king in the center of the board, the weak d3-pawn, better development and a pawn extra for White, this is completely winning for us.  Our queen has many squares to move to and we can even look to capture the pawn on d3, play Bc2, perhaps Nc3 and d4 later! Black is utterly busted, with inactive pieces asleep on the kingside.  We can simply capture on d3 next move with two extra pawns and, due to the aforementioned reasons, a completely winning position. }
