[White "2 - Réti Gambit Declined - 1... d5"]
[Black "[8] 8 - Réti Gambit Declined -  The Ambitious 2... d4 with 3... Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. e3
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
3... Nc6
{ The most precise defense from Black, although very rarely played  (only 8% of the time.)   It might seem a bit counterintuitive to defend the pawn with a piece instead of a pawn, but the idea is that now b4 is prevented, we won't get d4 in and Black can look to solidify with 4... e5.  In this variation we can only play for an equal-ish position, but that's okay! We can't expect a repertoire with fireworks and quick wins with no way at all for Black to equalize :P }
4. exd4
{ Releasing the tension straight away and preparing to simplify and get into an equal endgame. }
4... Nxd4 5. Nxd4 Qxd4 6. Nc3
{ We develop our knight to block the queen from eyeing our b2 pawn, which will be important for our next couple of moves. }
6... e5
{ Black grabs a lot of space in the center and opens up for their bishops. } 7.
d3
{ We support our c4 pawn with a pawn, also preventing 7... e4, and most importantly preparing to kick away the queen with 8. Be3 }
7... Nf6
{ This move is actually not the best, but the best move has never seen play in practice for casuals, as it's extremely unintuitive.   EDIT: I used to give 7... Nh6! as Black's best response, but I actually think that:   7...Ne7!  is Black's best resource, where they're preparing Nf5 and not allowing Bxh6.  Be2!  the plan I gave before against Nh6 with Be3 and d4 doesn't work for us, so this would be a better try, played twice with 2 wins at an average rating of 2432  Nf5  g4!  only played once, where White won, which perhaps even makes Nf5 at this point a little inaccurate.  Nh4  Rg1  with Be3 coming next, we have equalized and we get our d4 pawn-break in anyhow! }
8. Be3 Qd8 9. Be2
{ We have developed our bishops and will look to castle next. } 9... Be7
{ Black follows suit. } 10. O-O O-O 11. d4
{ The last couple of moves could also have happened in a different order, we didn't need to play 9. Be2 and 10. O-O before 11. d4, but I have chosen this move order, as I believe it's the most logical and simplest.  There's also an absolute ocean of alternative moves for White, but this seems to be the most intuitive. We want to open up the position for our bishops. }
11... exd4 12. Qxd4
{ We don't mind trading queens getting into an equal endgame. } 12... Qxd4 13.
Bxd4
{ This is just a very drawish position  (buuuuh, I know!)   It wasn't possible to find a better continuation against 3... Nc6, as it's both the best move and very rarely played, meaning it's difficult to play for an advantage and unreasonable to spend a lot of time studying it.  We can look to put our rooks on the open files and perhaps play for b3 and a4, to at least try to spice it up a bit. It's also possible to shuffle our pieces around with moves like Bd3, Be3, Ne2-Ng3, as we have plenty of time.  Because of the aforementioned reasons, we will stop our analysis here. }
