[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2 - Réti Gambit Declined - 1... d5"]
[Black "[9] 1 - Réti Gambit Declined -  The Slav 2... c6 with 4... Bg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4
{ All the moves so far have been explained in the 'Introduction to 1.. d5' in the introduction chapter.  Introduction to 1.. d5 }
2... c6
{ This is an interesting, although, passive try.   Black is aiming for a Slav-like position, which we will deny them by staying in Réti territory, in order to take them out of their comfort zone. }
3. e3
{ We grab more control of the d4 square. This is two-fold, as we prepare to develop our second knight without it getting booted away by d4, and we also prepare to recapture the pawn with our bishop, as Black was threatening to capture on c4 followed by b5, if we didn't play e3.  Black prepared to take on c4, because they had already played c6, which makes a difference compared to the 2... dxc4 and 3... b5 variations. For example:   3.Nc3  dxc4  e3  b5  a4  b4!  This leads Black in a fairly comfortable equal position and us in a very odd position, that we would never reach otherwise. }
3... Nf6 4. Nc3
{ Now we develop our second knight putting pressure in the center of the board.  This also leaves us quite a bit better after most of the common moves by Black. }
4... Bg4
{ Black develops their bishop and pins our knight.  These kinds of bishop pins are extremely common for casual players, this has a playrate of 43%, but they often aren't the most critical variations.  I personally believe White is already in the driver's seat, yet again. }
5. Qb3
{ This move breaks the pin on our knight, pressures both the d5- and the b7-pawn.   At this point Black can give up all hopes to transpose into a variation he knows with d4.  Black only has two options here to not be much worse: The extremely rare and also quite bad 5... Bc8 or the move we cover here. }
5... Qb6
{ The absolute best move, although this isn't reflected in the play-rate, which is 30%.  Black is getting ready to trade queens, which will stop both of our threats. }
6. Qxb6 { We simply capture and go into a better endgame. } 6... axb6 7. cxd5
{ The most forcing line. } 7... Bxf3
{ Black will often play this sooner or later. } 8. gxf3 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 cxd5 10.
Bb5+ Nc6 11. f4
{ We stop Black from expanding in the center and now White just has a slight edge and an easier position to play. Ideas include a4, b3, Bb2, Rg1, Ke2, d4 and h4, depending on what Black plays.   Black's doubled b-pawns are extremely poor, especially if more pieces get traded off, and our king has a great shelter on e2.  While this isn't a much better position, it's a pleasant endgame with the bishop pair and Black has doubled-isolated pawns, not to mention, this is with good play from Black. }
