1. Nf3 d5 2. c4
{ All the moves so far have been explained in the 'Introduction to 1.. d5' in the introduction chapter.  Introduction to 1.. d5 }
2... c6
{ This is an interesting, although slightly passive, try.  Black is aiming for a Slav position, which we will deny him by staying in Réti territory, in order to take Black out of his comfort zone. }
3. e3
{ We grab more control of the d4 square. This is two-fold, as we prepare to develop our second knight without it getting booted away by d4, and we also prepare to recapture the pawn with our bishop, as Black was threatening to capture on c4 followed by b5, if we didn't play e3.  Black prepared to take on c4, because they had already played c6, which makes a difference compared to the 2... dxc4 and 3... b5 variations. For example:   3.Nc3  dxc4  e3  b5  a4  b4!  This leads Black in a fairly comfortable equal position and us in a very odd position, that we would never reach otherwise. }
3... Nf6 4. Nc3
{ Now we develop our second knight, putting pressure in the center of the board.  This also leaves us quite a bit better after most of the common moves by Black. }
4... e6
{ A very solid setup, which seems quite passive for casual players, since it's not clear what to do with Black's light-squared bishop at all.   This setup is rather uncommon from Black, where they now will follow up with ideas like Be7, Bd6, Nbd7.  The mentioned ideas are more-or-less the only options for Black and therefore we'll meet the far majority of Black's tries the same way.  This position can also be reached via a different move order:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  d5  c4  e6  e3  Nf6  Nc3  c6 }
5. b3
{ We simply open up the best diagonal for our bishop and don't clarify the situation in the center with d4.  This move scores over 60% for White, so it seems to suggest, that Black players aren't aware of how to play against this. }
5... Nbd7
{ There's multiple move-orders and slight changes Black can do here, we'll just look at this one sample line as we're already looking at a side line of a side line.    5...Bb4  This popular move doesn't seem too threatening at all  Bb2  O-O  a3  Bc5  d4!  White now has a beautiful center and clearly stands better, partially due to Black's poor-looking bishops. }
6. Bb2
{ Getting the bishop to the most active diagonal and not developing our light-squared bishop too early, as continuations might arise where our bishop would like to recapture our c4 pawn - as for now - we'd like to recapture with our pawn though, strengthening our center and not allowing b5 with tempo. }
6... Bd6 { Other moves are also possible. } 7. Qc2
{ We stay very flexible and just develop our queen to its ideal square.  If you have any other preferences in these positions, feel free to go for those instead. Black's setup isn't very threatening and most setups by us work. }
7... O-O
{ If Black ever plays e5, we meet it in the same fashion:   7...e5  cxd5  Nxd5  This is the only move for Black, as cxd5 would allow Nb5 and Rc1  Ne4  With interesting play for White. }
8. Be2
{ All of our other pieces were on their ideal squares, and since we're looking to castle our king, now we move the light-squared bishop.  Our setup is extremely solid and seems more logical than Black's, as their bishop still looks very awkward on c8 and White's position is very flexible.  This position is still quite equal and none really stands better, though I'd prefer White, especially for casual players and it makes no sense to learn more 'hardcore' and 'punishing' moves by White, as this is a rare side line of a side line and quite soft to play against. }
