1. Nf3 d5 2. c4
{ All the moves so far have been explained in the 'Introduction to 1.. d5' in the introduction chapter.  Introduction to 1.. d5 }
2... c6
{ This is an interesting, although, passive try.   Black is aiming for a Slav-like position, which we will deny them by staying in Réti territory, in order to take them out of their comfort zone. }
3. e3
{ We grab more control of the d4 square. This is two-fold, as we prepare to develop our second knight without it getting booted away by d4, and we also prepare to recapture the pawn with our bishop, as Black was threatening to capture on c4 followed by b5, if we didn't play e3.  Black prepared to take on c4, because they had already played c6, which makes a difference compared to the 2... dxc4 and 3... b5 variations. For example:   3.Nc3  dxc4  e3  b5  a4  b4!  This leads Black in a fairly comfortable equal position and us in a very odd position, that we would never reach otherwise. }
3... Bg4
{ Black develops their bishop and pins our knight.  These kinds of bishop pins are extremely common for casual players, this move has a 20% play-rate, but they often aren't the most critical variations, especially not when they arrive this early. }
4. Qb3
{ We develop our queen the same way as in the variation with our knight on c3 and Black's knight on f6. }
4... Qc7
{ This time 4... Qc7 is actually the best move.  Make sure to not fall into Black's trap, as we don't have a knight on c3 and the bishop on c1 is undefended!   5.cxd5  cxd5  Qxd5  Qxc1+  Where Black is completely winning }
5. Ne5
{ This is a tricky move, as it's a game-losing move to capture our knight, which is the most obvious and most played move!  Since it's not possible for Black to capture our knight, he has to move his bishop somewhere, where we then - finally - play d4, grabbing a big center and our knight can always fall back to f3, if needed.  This position is slightly better and more comfortable for White, even with this extremely practically challenging move! }
5... Qxe5
{ Trying to punish our 'mistake' is a blunder by Black.    5...dxc4??  This is another possible blunder.  Bxc4!  With the threats of taking on f7, b7 and the bishop on g4, White is completely winning. }
6. Qxb7
{ Oops! Black is simply losing a rook, and with it, the game!  At this point I would like to thank all the Black players who kindly walk into our traps; you are greatly appreciated :D }
