[White "2 - Réti Gambit Declined - 1... d5"]
[Black "[13] 1 - Réti Gambit Declined - The French 2... e6 with 4... c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4
{ All the moves so far have been explained in the 'Introduction to 1.. d5' in the introduction chapter.  Introduction to 1.. d5 }
2... e6
{ Black has the same setup as in the French, although this exact position usually arises from an English opening.  This is a solid continuation for Black, but the same issue haunts Black as in the normal French. What to do with the light-squared bishop?  This setup doesn't have much standalone potential, compared to our other variations, as it very often transposes.  Because of this, we'll only look at the standalone tries, where it doesn't transpose to something we've already covered. }
3. e3 { The same move as always, asking Black if they wish to transpose. } 3...
Nf6 4. Nc3 { Again, same move as we play in other variations. } 4... c5
{ Black doesn't want to transpose into any other variation and instead follows through with the common French structure of c5, d5 and e6.   NOTE: A student of the course told me that while  4...Be7  is the third most popular move, it is the by far most popular on the higher levels, so I decided to mention it here in a clickable ^^  5.b3!?  as always, we want to stay away from d4 unless we have a very good reason to play it, as else we would transpose to a mainline Queen's Gambit Declined.  5...O-O  almost exclusively played  6.Bb2  getting our bishop established on the fantastic diagonal  6...c5!?  now this seems critical, as the idea of d4, as we played here in the text, has less value once we already have a pawn on b3 and bishop on b2.  7.cxd5!  let us meet it in the same way as in the text move, to keep things simple!  7...exd5  this is the most popular, but I actually think 7... Nxd5! is better, where we play 8. Qc2 with an interesting position, but now we have  8.d4!  same move as in the text  8...Nc6  and now after  9.Be2!  White scores over 65% in both the 1600 online and the Masters OTB database. }
5. cxd5
{ The simplest continuation our goal will be to isolate Black's d-pawn and get an easier position to play. }
5... exd5 6. d4
{ This helps us with our idea to isolate Black's d-pawn and target it later on in the game. }
6... Nc6 7. Bb5
{ The most obvious square for our light-squared bishop, which also pins Black's knight.  It's not clear what to do with our dark-squared bishop yet, so we simply focus on the rest of our pieces and castle before making our mind up. }
7... Bd7
{ The most played move and probably also the most logical.  Black both prepares to recapture on c6 with their bishop, so they don't ruin their pawn structure, and also unpins their knight.    7...a6  Bxc6  bxc6  O-O  cxd4  exd4  This doesn't seem very challenging and should be fairly straight forward to play. We have an isolated pawn, but Black's d- and c-pawn are both more or less tamed by our single d-pawn. }
8. O-O a6 9. Be2
{ While it's definitely possible to capture Black's knight, they have spent a tempo getting the bishop on d7 to recapture and also plays a6 to provoke the capture.   Since Black has spent time preparing for our capture on c6 and since we don't want to just give up the bishop pair, we retreat our bishop to the most logical square, not interrupting our queen's defense of the d4 pawn.  This also prepares a trap! }
9... Be7 { The most played move, falling for our trap! } 10. dxc5
{ Now there's no way for Black to defend the d5 pawn, as the bishop on d7 is blocking his queen's defense of the pawn! }
10... Bxc5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Qxd5
{ There's some other possible tries from Black, but since this is a sideline of a sideline, the positions are quite simple to play and it's rarely reached, we won't spend more energy on these other tries.  The most important for us is to remember this trap of winning the pawn! }
