[White "2 - Réti Gambit Declined - 1... d5"]
[Black "[14] 2 - Réti Gambit Declined - The French 2... e6 with 4... Bb4"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4
{ All the moves so far have been explained in the 'Introduction to 1.. d5' in the introduction chapter.  Introduction to 1.. d5 }
2... e6
{ Black has the same setup as in the French, although this exact position usually arises from an English opening.  This is a solid continuation for Black, but the same issue haunts Black as in the normal French. What to do with the light-squared bishop?  This setup doesn't have much standalone potential, compared to our other variations, as it very often transposes.  Because of this, we'll only look at the standalone tries, where it doesn't transpose to something we've already covered. }
3. e3 { The same move as always, asking Black if they wish to transpose. } 3...
Nf6 4. Nc3 { Again, same move as we play in other variations. } 4... Bb4
{ This invites White to play d4 and transpose into a very well-known theoretical line of the Nimzo-Indian.  We haven't committed the pawn to d4 yet though, and therefore there's no pin on our knight on c3 and we haven't spent time placing a pawn on d4. We use this to reach a unique position instead! }
5. a3
{ Putting a question to the bishop immediately.  It's possible for Black to simply retreat the bishop, but then it would just look silly to have gone there in the first place! Especially because b4 is even a possibility in some cases. }
5... Bxc3 6. bxc3
{ We capture with the b-pawn to strengthen the center and open up the b-file for us to potentially use. }
6... O-O
{ This seems the most obvious, also because White was ready to capture back on c4 in case Black captured. }
7. cxd5 { We get rid of our doubled-pawns. } 7... exd5
{ The best and most played capture.     7...Nxd5  c4  Nf6  d4  is also possible but somehow seems a little more awkward. }
8. c4
{ We challenge Black's center yet again, using our extra center pawns.  This also opens up the possibility of Bb2 and d4, getting a very nice grip on the position and we just have more space and more clear plans.  In my opinion, this position is borderline much better for White and I would love to see this in my own games, but unfortunately, I think it's only objectively slightly better.   In other words: While the odds might only be slightly in our favor, I would definitely place my bet on White! }
