[Black "[15] 1 - Réti Gambit Declined - The Conservative 2... Nf6 with 3... Nxd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4
{ All the moves so far have been explained in the 'Introduction to 1.. d5' in the introduction chapter.  Introduction to 1.. d5 }
2... Nf6
{ This move just isn't very good.  Black will experience the same issue as they would in a typical Scandinavian position. }
3. cxd5
{ Forcing a knight or queen into the middle of the board on the d5 square, where we will harass it, either with our knight  (if queen takes)  or with our pawn  (if knight takes) }
3... Nxd5
{ This move is the most obvious, not allowing us to develop our knight with tempo on the queen.  We do, however, have our other aforementioned idea to take advantage of the knight capturing. }
4. e4
{ Grabbing space in the center and opening up for our light-squared bishop. }
4... Nb6
{ Probably the most logical move from Black, as the knight would have been harassed on f6. }
5. d4
{ We grab even more control of the center, gaining a big chunk of the center and opening up squares for our pieces.  I mean, just look at the position! How can you not already be very happy? :D }
5... Bg4
{ The most obvious try for Black, developing their bishop with a pin on our knight before eventually moving the e-pawn and also putting pressure on our d4 pawn.    5...e6  Nc3  Bb4  a3  Bxc3+  bxc3  This position is also much better for White and we should have a very easy game. }
6. Be2
{ We simply break the pin, prepare to recapture the knight with our bishop  (not dropping the pawn on d4, as we would after queen captures)  and also prepare to castle. }
6... e6
{ Opening up the eyes of the dark-squared bishop, also preparing to castle in two moves. }
7. Be3
{ We develop our other bishop where it's sitting nice and comfortably watching our center pawn. From e3 our bishop also stops Black from playing c5 and there's no reason to rush castling, as we'll see in this variation.  Our setup is extremely solid and very flexible, so we'll play these moves against almost any moves from Black. }
7... Bb4+
{ Getting ready to pin our knight  (as we will develop it to block the check)  and castling kingside. }
8. Nc3 O-O 9. O-O
{ White is simply doing fantastic in this position with the far better center and active pieces.  Our setup is very flexible and we're ready to start making progress how we see fit. We can keep our lead with developing moves such as: a3, Qb3, Rfe1, Rad1 and h3, centering the rooks and getting rid of annoying pins.  It's not clear what Black can even do in this position, as both their bishops are essentially on the best squares, our center is fortified and both e5 and c5 hangs a pawn. You really can't ask for much more out of the opening! }
