1. Nf3 d5 2. c4
{ All the moves so far have been explained in the 'Introduction to 1.. d5' in the introduction chapter.  Introduction to 1.. d5 }
2... Nf6
{ This move just isn't very good.  Black will experience the same issue as they would in a typical Scandinavian position. }
3. cxd5
{ Forcing a knight or queen into the middle of the board on the d5 square, where we will harass it, either with our knight  (if queen takes)  or with our pawn  (if knight takes) }
3... Qxd5
{ This simply leads to a better Scandinavian for White, as we've succesfully traded our c-pawn for Black's center d-pawn, allowing us to establish an even greater pawn-presence in the center of the board. }
4. Nc3
{ We start by getting a tempo on the Black queen and preparing ideas of e4. }
4... Qd8
{ Though this is the most popular move, played around 50% of the time, I don't believe it to be as testing as   4...Qa5  Which we will look at in the next variation.  This is also supported by White already having a 62% winrate in this position! }
5. e4
{ This is the main difference between the normal Scandinavian and what we're playing.   Since we still have our e-pawn, we'll grab a lot of space and control in the center by pushing forward our d- and e-pawn. }
5... Nc6
{ Black develops their knight and tries to pressure the d-pawn once it lands on d4, perhaps even intending e5. }
6. d4
{ We stop ideas of e5 and claim an even larger portion of the center.  Surely, we must already be better here with our center pawns! :D   (The engine is already saying roughly +2 in this position, so, we could in fact just stop here and say: 'That's winning!') }
6... Bg4
{ Black could also have played this before 5... Nc6, but it doesn't change much.  White is, like mentioned on the previous move, already completely winning in this position, but this position is even more-so winning due to a very nice tactical shot! }
7. d5
{ Grabbing further control of the center and making the c6 knight feel extremely uncomfortable. }
7... Ne5
{ Wait a minute, did we blunder!?  Our knight is now pinned and attacked and it looks like Black is getting great play!  (Don't worry, they're not!)     7...Bxf3  gxf3  Ne5  f4  Ned7  e5  This position is also completely winning for White. }
8. Nxe5
{ BAM! We are giving up our queen!  At this point I would like to apologize to the future opponents, who you will crush in this variation, as it's almost unfair how strong this continuation is. I wouldn't be surprised if you get hurled a few 'cheater!' remarks at you after this brilliant tactical shot :P }
8... Bxd1 { What else? } 9. Bb5+
{ The good moves just keep coming. There's now no way for Black to defend his king without giving up the queen. }
9... c6 { Trying to stop our killer bishop } 10. dxc6
{ Black will still lose their queen in every line, due to our killer bishop. }
10... a6
{ 10...bxc6  Bxc6+  Qd7  Bxd7+  Nxd7  Nxd7  This is also completely winning for White   10...Qc7  cxb7+  Kd8  Nxf7#  White could also capture the rook on a8 and promote to a queen with check.  All lines here simply win for White! If you want to, you can analyze a bit deeper with the engine, but I don't think you'll need more preparation than these variations. }
11. c7+ { Discovered check means Black can't save their queen. } 11... axb5 12.
cxd8=Q+ { Winning back the queen. } 12... Rxd8 13. Nxd1
{ Now we also get a piece! } 13... Nxe4 14. O-O
{ The position is completely winning for White now, as we're a piece up and ready to develop the rest of our pieces, while Black's pieces are extremely passive and they're a full piece behind.  This is, in all honesty, already resignable for Black. }
