[White "3 - Réti Mirrored - 1... Nf6"]
[Black "Introduction to Chapter"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6
{ Welcome to the informational variation surrounding the move 1... Nf6, which I've dubbed 'Réti Mirrored'.  This is the second most popular move for Black at the lower ratings. As explained in the informationalOpening Database, the move Nf6 is played roughly 13% of the time. Therefore, you can expect to see this position fairly often.  Black copies White and simply develops his king-side knight, not committing to a certain pawn structure and letting us move a pawn first. As 2... d5 is definitely still an option for Black, and we don't want to play 2. e3 against a setup with g6, it makes most sense to start by committing our pawn to c4. }
2. c4
{ Any other move would allow Black to play 2... d5, where we would be out of theory.  Now the move 2... d5 would transpose to the first chapter: Réti Gambit Declined with Nf6, meaning variation15,16,17 and18.  There's also the possibility of 2... g6, which is the most popular option by far and what we'll cover in this chapter, though it could also be reached from the 1... g6 move-order.  Other lesser played tries include 2... e6 and 2... d6, where we will play 3. e3 to, yet again, allow transpositions to familiar positions.  It's important to always be on the lookout for potential transpositions, as there's a lot of different move orders Black can play.   2...c5  will take us out of our repertoire and transpose to a symmetrical English, however  3.Nc3  Nc6  g3  Should still be fairly straight forward to play, even if you're unfamiliar with the English, which is supported by a 56% winrate. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3 - Réti Mirrored - 1... Nf6"]
[Black "[1] 1 - Réti Mirrored -  2... g6 The Slow 6... Nbd7 with 7... e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4
{ For explanations, check the informationalIntroduction to chapter } 2... g6
{ The is the most common move, played around 35% of the time. Now we're in territory that could also arise from 1... g6.  After moves like 2... e6 and 2... c6, we play 3. e3 and Black has nothing better than transpose to our second chapter - The Retí Gambit: Declined - with the move d5.  Other lesser - and weaker - tries are only mentioned in the puzzles chapter, so make sure to check it out! }
3. d4
{ We're looking to claim an even larger stake of the center with this move and only then fianchetto our bishop. This way we not only get a mirrored kingside, but also a better center, which will very often lead to a simply better position.  This is one of the few times we play a 'normal' d4 opening, but we will spice it up with the mentioned kingside fianchetto and also only commit to d4 after Black has comitted to g6.   We're also trying to discourage c5, which does still work, but incredibly hard - and rare - for beginners to spot. }
3... Bg7
{ The obviously most played move, being played roughly 85% of the time. Why else would Black play g6?  Black will almost exclusively play Bg7 and O-O before comitting to any pawn pushes, and since we're not gonna push any center pawns during the next few moves, this makes sense for Black to play.  If Black doesn't play g6, they'll almost exclusively play d6  (ending up playing g6 later anyway)  or d5, which allows the thematic:   3...d5  cxd5  where we either get a tempo on the knight with e4 or the queen with Nc3, very reminiscent ofthis puzzle. }
4. g3 { Following through with our plan. } 4... O-O
{ Black gets their early castling and will prepare to push the pawns and strike back in the center very soon. }
5. Bg2 d6
{ The by-far most played move at lower levels, played over 60% of the time. Black is preparing to play either e5 or c5, and will often start by planting their knight on d7 to support these breaks.  It's not possible for Black to just lay back and never move the pawns, as they'd just get an absolutely abysmal position, so these two breaks also seem like the most natural thing for Black to play for. }
6. Nc3
{ We look to further strengthen our center before castling and the two only real challenging moves are the 3rd and 4th most played, meaning we often get a great position through this move order. }
6... Nbd7
{ Black follows through with their plan, which is also the most logical and popular, even though there's multiple better choices, this can be argued to be more sharp and ambitious for Black.  We will, however, soon see why this isn't a very critical variation. }
7. O-O
{ Now that we've developed our pieces towards the center, we simply castle, getting our king to safety and enjoying a near picture perfect position.  We allow Black to strike however they wish, for us to then answer the threats precisely and keep our advantage. }
7... e5
{ The most logical and popular move by Black, played around 35% of the time.  Black is grabbing their share of the center and trying to provoke us to capture the pawn on e5. }
8. e4
{ This is a stronger move than simply capturing the pawn on e5, as we grab further control of the center, don't allow Black to massively trade on e5 - as they would if we captured - and prepare to recapture on d4 with our knight. }
8... exd4
{ The most logical move, not allowing us to have three great pawns in the center, and why else play e5? }
9. Nxd4
{ We recapture with the knight, getting it further into the center and also opening up the possibility of moving our f-pawn.   9...c5  Ndb5  This mix of c5 and e5 doesn't work and White just has a winning position due to the pawn falling on d6. }
9... Ne5
{ The most played move, trying to active the knight.   9...Nc5  b3  Re8  f3  This leads to a very similar position.   9...Re8  Be3  Ne5  b3  This also leads to a very similar position. }
10. b3
{ We simply defend our c4 pawn and potentially prepare to place our bishop on b2. }
10... Bg4
{ The most played move, where Black is trying to say they get a tempo on our queen, but here it's nice that we can move our f-pawn. }
11. f3
{ After this move White just has a superior position. We have great pieces and a significantly better center.  Our dark-square bishop can be developed to either b2, e3 or g5, depending on what you prefer. This is the picture perfect setup we aim for against similar positions with c5, Re8 and Nc5, as there's no weaknesses for us after e4, f3 and b3.  Potential moves after developing the bishop for White include: Qd2, Rad1, Rc1 and Ndb5. }
