3. d4
{ We're looking to claim an even larger stake of the center with this move and only then fianchetto our bishop. This way we not only get a mirrored kingside, but also a better center, which will very often lead to a simply better position.  This is one of the few times we play a 'normal' d4 opening, but we will spice it up with the mentioned kingside fianchetto and also only commit to d4 after Black has comitted to g6.   We're also trying to discourage c5, which does still work, but incredibly hard - and rare - for beginners to spot. }
3... Bg7
{ The obviously most played move, being played roughly 85% of the time. Why else would Black play g6?  Black will almost exclusively play Bg7 and O-O before comitting to any pawn pushes, and since we're not gonna push any center pawns during the next few moves, this makes sense for Black to play.  If Black doesn't play g6, they'll almost exclusively play d6  (ending up playing g6 later anyway)  or d5, which allows the thematic:   3...d5  cxd5  where we either get a tempo on the knight with e4 or the queen with Nc3, very reminiscent ofthis puzzle. }
4. g3 { Following through with our plan. } 4... O-O
{ Black gets their early castling and will prepare to push the pawns and strike back in the center very soon. }
5. Bg2 d6
{ The by-far most played move at lower levels, played over 60% of the time. Black is preparing to play either e5 or c5, and will often start by planting their knight on d7 to support these breaks.  It's not possible for Black to just lay back and never move the pawns, as they'd just get an absolutely abysmal position, so these two breaks also seem like the most natural thing for Black to play for. }
6. Nc3
{ We look to further strengthen our center before castling and the two only real challenging moves are the 3rd and 4th most played, meaning we often get a great position through this move order. }
6... Nc6
{ This variation isn't vastly different from its 6... Nbd7 counter-part, though there will be further pressure on d4 after e5. }
7. O-O
{ Now that we've developed our pieces towards the center, we simply castle, getting our king to safety.  We allow Black to strike with 7... e5, but we are ready to handle this. }
7... e5
{ The only real ambitious move for Black, why else develop the knight to c6?   7...Bg4  This can be met in numerous ways, for example, h3 or d5 for White. }
8. dxe5
{ A notable difference from what we play against 6... Nbd7 due to   8.e4  Bg4!  Pinning our knight, as the bishop isn't blocked by a knight on d7, also preparing to capture on d4.  It was also possible to instead play 8. d5, but I found this to be easier to understand. }
8... Nxe5
{ The slightly more popular recapture, daring White to go into an endgame, though we don't mind this at all.   8...dxe5  Bg5  This looks very similar to the position we reach anyway, playing for Bxf6 and Nd5 }
9. Nxe5
{ Simplifying and getting into a good endgame, where Black falls into our traps almost every single game. }
9... dxe5 10. Qxd8 Rxd8 11. Bg5
{ We create a deadly pin, which almost always wins at least a pawn. } 11... c6
{ Mistake that simply lets White get a winning edge. The second most popular move   11...h6  Bxf6  Bxf6  Nd5  also wins a pawn for White on c7 and is therefore still significantly better for us. }
12. Ne4
{ Black can't defend the knight and if they move it, we'll capture their rook.  White will either win a piece or the exchange, both with a winning position. }
