3... Bg7
{ The obviously most played move, being played roughly 85% of the time. Why else would Black play g6?  Black will almost exclusively play Bg7 and O-O before comitting to any pawn pushes, and since we're not gonna push any center pawns during the next few moves, this makes sense for Black to play.  If Black doesn't play g6, they'll almost exclusively play d6  (ending up playing g6 later anyway)  or d5, which allows the thematic:   3...d5  cxd5  where we either get a tempo on the knight with e4 or the queen with Nc3, very reminiscent ofthis puzzle. }
4. g3 { Following through with our plan. } 4... O-O
{ Black gets their early castling and will prepare to push the pawns and strike back in the center very soon. }
5. Bg2 d6
{ The by-far most played move at lower levels, played over 60% of the time. Black is preparing to play either e5 or c5, and will often start by planting their knight on d7 to support these breaks.  It's not possible for Black to just lay back and never move the pawns, as they'd just get an absolutely abysmal position, so these two breaks also seem like the most natural thing for Black to play for. }
6. Nc3
{ We look to further strengthen our center before castling and the two only real challenging moves are the 3rd and 4th most played, meaning we often get a great position through this move order. }
6... c5
{ Black strikes in the center immediately and doesn't spend time putting their knight on d7.   It's also possible to get a very similar position through   5...c5  Nc3 }
7. O-O
{ Getting our king to safety and preparing to recapture on d4, if needed. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4
{ We already have a promising position, especially since the most popular - and critical - variation is hard to play for Black. }
8... Nc6
{ What!? At first glance, this is just hanging a pawn. However, Black gets full compensation for it, and this is actually both the best and the most popular variation!  Luckily for us, most Black players fail to prove their compensation and we'll therefore very often run away with a great position! }
9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bxc6
{ We accept the pawn offered to us and ask Black to prove their compensation. }
10... Rb8 11. Bg2
{ Retreating our bishop and preparing to stabilize with moves like Rb1 and Qc2 }
11... Bb7
{ This is NOT the way to go. Black simply plays as if they hadn't lost a pawn and allows us to keep playing sensibly and enjoy our extra pawn.  The only critical move from Black was   11...Qa5!  Qd2  Be6!  Where Black has a lot of compensation and it's difficult to stay ahead as White, though this is extremely rare - and also difficult - for Black to play. }
12. Rb1
{ White is simply much better as we have no real weaknesses and we're prepared to play moves like Qc2, Bd2 and b3, keeping everything defended and enjoying our extra pawn. }
