[White "3 - Réti Mirrored - 1... Nf6"]
[Black "[7] 1 - Réti Mirrored - 2... e6 The Queen's Indian 3... b6"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6
{ When I first created this course, I decided to not cover 2... e6 or 1... e6, as I correctly noted that it will almost exclusively transpose after the eventual d5, but there is another trickier try available to Black. }
3. e3
{ A necessary move to stay within our repertoire after the most popular move   3...d5  Nc3  this is covered in the important variationRéti Gambit Declined - The French 2... e6 with 4... c5 }
3... b6
{ This is the tricky try I was talking about! The setup Black is employing is equivalent to that of the Queen's Indian Defense, which is an opening often played against 1. d4 & 2. c4.   This is only played 10% of the time in this position, which is even rarer since 2... e6 is also only played 20% of the time as well. This is why I initially refrained from covering it, and why the informational variations mention how I don't cover anything against e6.   Unfortunately, this setup is quite potent against ours and multiple students of the course have pointed this out to me, as they've faced it in their own games. Because of this, I decided to create this small trainable for these individuals and for whoever may have to face it in the future as well. Enjoy! ^^ }
4. g3
{ While it is definitely possible to go for the more classical 4. d4, this transposes into a non-critical variation of the QID and allows Black many popular, testing options, so we opt for this rare move instead! }
4... Bb7 { Played exclusively. } 5. Bg2
{ We now have pacified Black's light-squared bishop and can look to castle short as well. }
5... Be7
{ Note how 5... c5 doesn't change much and how after   5...d5  cxd5  exd5  O-O  we're completely fine and have a slight edge. }
6. O-O O-O 7. d4
{ I've decided to go for this move, even though it allows a few options for Black, as I believe the interesting 7. b3!? to be too unthematic to recommend, though it's certainly a fun option.   I think we already have a strong center and Black has to start challenging it to not be worse. }
7... d6
{ This is the most popular move, tried 30% of the time, but doesn't work very well, as Black isn't making threats in the center of the board.   Note how after 7... d5, we capture on d5, and after 7... c5, we capture on c5. In both positions, we also look to play 9. b3 and 10. Bb2 after. }
8. Nc3
{ Even though this is not the most challenging move objectively, Black has to find   8...Ne4!  to not be worse, which has only been found 2.5% of the time, and we're still slightly better after  Ne2 }
8... Nbd7 { This is played over 75% of the time, but simply fails. } 9. d5
{ We strike in the center and already get a sizeable edge due to Black's now horrible bishops on b7 and e7.   If Black doesn't immediately answer with 9... e5 or 9... exd5, we can look to play 10. Nd4, against 9... exd5, we will capture back with the pawn before playing 11. Nd4 or 11. dxc6 and against 9... e5, we have an ocean of good moves, like 10. e4.   I hope that this makes you feel ready to face this rare pesky setup, and if not quite, I hope it at least provides a good starting point for further analysis on your part! }
