[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4 - Mikenas Defense - 1... Nc6"]
[Black "Introduction to Chapter"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nc6
{ The Mikenas/Nimzowitsch Defense!  Serious followers of this move usually play this knight move against absolutely everything White throws at them, in order to try to trick White and get them out of their comfort zone.   I was skeptical when I first saw this move, as it was played a very high percentage of the time, especially compared to the higher/highest level. I can say, that after investigating the move for a while, it's now clear to me, that Black actually usually doesn't know any of the theory here and very often just plays subpar and/or easy variations to play against!  This means that we should be very thankful whenever we see this move on the board! }
2. d4
{ This could also arise from a Mikenas Defense, where we start with 1. d4, but the main difference here is that most of the casual players who play this knight move actually aren't aware of this transposition!  They suddenly get confused and scratch their head after we play 2. d4 as they realize that they in fact do not play this way against 1. d4, and are therefore already left on their own from this point forward.  We will look to fully abuse this and gain many quick wins, as is supported by a 57% winrate from this position! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4 - Mikenas Defense - 1... Nc6"]
[Black "[1] 1 - Mikenas Defense - The Simple 2... d5 with 3... dxc4"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
2... d5
{ A rather poor move, but there's not much else to play for Black, as White was threatening to play d5 and   2...e6  just allows  3.e4  with a great position.   Black simply gets a worse version of a Queen's Gambit, as the knight doesn't feel at home on c6, as it's completely blocking the c-pawn.  This does have tricky ideas on higher levels, namely the Chigorin with 3... Bg4, but on anything below the higher levels, it's usually just Black who got tricked and doesn't know what happened. }
3. c4
{ We take over the center straight away and get a simply better Queen's Gambit position due to Black's knight. }
3... dxc4
{ The most common move in the position, the engine also seems to like it, but this variation is extremely difficult for Black to play, which we'll see after our next move. }
4. d5
{ The beginning of what often becomes the end for Black, supported by the fact White scores over 70%  (!!)  from this position!  The knight on c6 is in a real dilemma and Qa4+ is a real threat, as well as the knight on f3 covering squares. }
4... Nb8
{ The best square for the knight, admitting its mistake, as there were no other real options. This is only played 40% of the time, so we can look to fully abuse the other moves by Black!  It should already be apparent why we choose to play this way against 1... Nc6, if these are the positions we get when our opponent chooses the right retreat. }
5. e4
{ Gaining a beautiful pawn-duo in the center and preparing to capture back on c4 with our bishop. }
5... e6
{ The most obvious and most played move by Black, simply attacking our pawn duo and opening up for their dark-squared bishop. }
6. Bxc4 { We simply recapture our c4 pawn and add another defender to d5. }
6... exd5
{ Taking one of the pawns in our pawn duo, also opening up the eyes for Black's light-squared bishop. }
7. Bxd5
{ We recapture with the bishop, eyeing both the f7 and b7 pawns.  This is the most tricky and ambitious way to recapture the pawn, although 7. exd4 is also fully playable. }
7... Nf6
{ This move is the best move available to Black, although not the most played, and in the majority of cases, Black even fails to realize why this move is the best.    7...c6  Bxf7+  Ke7  Qb3  The most played move 7... c6 leaves White at +7 with a completely winning position. This looks extremely similar to what we'll often get after 7... Nf6. }
8. Bxf7+
{ Now the real fireworks begin!  This is the objectively strongest move, as we grab a pawn, lure Black away from their queen and now ask Black to make a decision. }
8... Ke7
{ A huge blunder, but the by-far most played move! Black simply gives in to White's attack and misses their chance to just give up a single pawn and avoid an objectively game-winning attack from White.    8...Kxf7  Qxd8  Bb4+!  This is the tactic Black had to see, where White will still be a pawn up with a better position after:  Qd2  Bxd2  Nbxd2  . }
9. Qb3
{ With the Black king stuck in the center, also blocking the f8 bishop and White being able to develop all the pieces harmoniously, Black is completely lost and White is roughly +6 according to the engine.  There's extremely many ways to win against every move Black can throw at us, and since there's no good or obvious moves for Black, it would take a very long time to analyse this position fully.  Because of this, I've decided to just leave the position here with a few comments. I hope you'll also enjoy finding your own plans and ideas to obliterate Black!   Potential moves for White include: Nc3, Bd2, Be3, e5, O-O, so basically just keep developing your pieces rationally and prepare to attack. There's no way for Black to develop their pieces or even get the king to a semi-safe square. }
