[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4 - Mikenas Defense - 1... Nc6"]
[Black "[2] 2 - Mikenas Defense - The Simple 2... d5 with 3... dxc4"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
2... d5
{ A rather poor move, but there's not much else to play for Black, as White was threatening to play d5 and   2...e6  just allows  3.e4  with a great position.   Black simply gets a worse version of a Queen's Gambit, as the knight doesn't feel at home on c6, as it's completely blocking the c-pawn.  This does have tricky ideas on higher levels, namely the Chigorin with 3... Bg4, but on anything below the higher levels, it's usually just Black who got tricked and doesn't know what happened. }
3. c4
{ We take over the center straight away and get a simply better Queen's Gambit position due to Black's knight. }
3... dxc4
{ The most common move in the position, the engine also seems to like it, but this variation is extremely difficult for Black to play, which we'll see after our next move. }
4. d5
{ The beginning of what often becomes the end for Black, supported by the fact White scores over 70%  (!!)  from this position!  The knight on c6 is in a real dilemma and Qa4+ is a real threat, as well as the knight on f3 covering squares. }
4... Nb8
{ The best square for the knight, admitting its mistake, as there were no other real options. This is only played 40% of the time, so we can look to fully abuse the other moves by Black!  It should already be apparent why we choose to play this way against 1... Nc6, if these are the positions we get when our opponent chooses the right retreat. }
5. e4
{ Gaining a beautiful pawn-duo in the center and preparing to capture back on c4 with our bishop. }
5... Nf6
{ This is the only real other try for Black - apart from 5... e6.   Black increases the pressure on the center and targets our e4 pawn.  We'll continue in a similar fashion to what we did in the other line, but here we'll just guard our e4 pawn first. }
6. Nc3
{ Simply developing our knight, defending our e4 pawn and strengthening the center. }
6... e6
{ What else to play? Black opens up for their dark-squared bishop and challenges our center.  It's also good to know this following mistake by Black:    6...Bg4?  Bxc4  e6  Qb3!  White is already much better in this position, as there's a fork between the pawns on b7 and e6, while we also get to keep our pawn-center intact. }
7. Bxc4
{ We simply recapture our pawn and add more protection to the d5 pawn, perhaps even preparing to play dxe6, if Black doesn't capture. }
7... exd5
{ The most logical move, opening up the eyes of Black's light-squared bishop and removing one of the pawns in our pawn duo. }
8. exd5
{ We choose to get an isolated pawn, but this isn't a regular isolated pawn!  This is an isolated pawn all the way on d5, stopping Be6 and Nc6, not to mention, it's defended 3 times! }
8... Bb4
{ This is the most played move by far, played 40% of the time, but it's actually a terrible blunder!  Some better tries could be:    8...Bd6  Qe2+  Be7  O-O  O-O  Bf4  Where White would just have a simple and slightly better position to play.    8...Bg4  O-O  Be7  h3  Where White, again, would just have a simple and slightly better position to play. }
9. Qa4+
{ The game-winning move!   It's not possible for Black to defend the bishop, as the pawn on d5 can capture in case of Nc6. }
