[Black "[5] 1 - Mikenas Defense - The Simple 2... d5 with 3... e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
2... d5
{ A rather poor move, but there's not much else to play for Black, as White was threatening to play d5 and   2...e6  just allows  3.e4  with a great position.   Black simply gets a worse version of a Queen's Gambit, as the knight doesn't feel at home on c6, as it's completely blocking the c-pawn.  This does have tricky ideas on higher levels, namely the Chigorin with 3... Bg4, but on anything below the higher levels, it's usually just Black who got tricked and doesn't know what happened. }
3. c4
{ We take over the center straight away and get a simply better Queen's Gambit position due to Black's knight. }
3... e6
{ This is one of the few times we play a 'regular d4 opening', as Black has committed their knight to c6, which is a bad square for the knight, and we can look to get a very pleasant opening with a nice advantage. }
4. e3
{ Like we've done so many times before in the course, preparing to recapture our pawn on c4. }
4... Nf6
{ The few times Black doesn't play this move immediately, they will almost always play it in the next couple of moves.    4...Bb4+  Nbd2  Nf6  This would transpose to the text move. }
5. Nbd2
{ This is a very nice move, though a lot of alternatives exist. The idea is to take advantage of Black's poor dark-squared bishop and also prepare Bd3, as we can now capture on c4 with our knight. }
5... Bb4
{ This seems to be the most natural square to develop and is therefore the most played move by far, but this just leaves White better. }
6. a3
{ Taking full advantage of Black's play!  We question Black's bishop and since our knight is on d2 and not c3, they can't double our pawns and we can recapture with our bishop.    6...Be7  Bd3  We're ready to castle and our knight is still defending the c4 pawn. Very similar position to the text move. }
6... Bxd2+
{ Why else play 5... Bb4? If Black was going to drop the bishop back to e7, it made more sense to develop it there in the first place. }
7. Bxd2 O-O 8. Rc1
{ We still want to recapture the c4 pawn with our bishop, in case of dxc4, but now our rook is also where it wants to be.   On our next moves we can look to play Bd3, Qc2 and O-O with a significantly better position due to the bishop pair, Black's horrendous light-squared bishop and our much better pieces. }
