[White "4 - Mikenas Defense - 1... Nc6"]
[Black "[6] 1 - Mikenas Defense - The Chigorin 2... d5 with 3... Bg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
2... d5
{ A rather poor move, but there's not much else to play for Black, as White was threatening to play d5 and   2...e6  just allows  3.e4  with a great position.   Black simply gets a worse version of a Queen's Gambit, as the knight doesn't feel at home on c6, as it's completely blocking the c-pawn.  This does have tricky ideas on higher levels, namely the Chigorin with 3... Bg4, but on anything below the higher levels, it's usually just Black who got tricked and doesn't know what happened. }
3. c4
{ We take over the center straight away and get a simply better Queen's Gambit position due to Black's knight. }
3... Bg4
{ The Chigorin. This may look like yet another dubious reply by Black, and while it objectively speaking is, it's been played in thousands of games between masters - even more at club level - with decent results at club level and at the highest levels in the faster time formats - and is undoubtedly the best try for Black after 1... Nc6.  If your opponent plays this 4th most played, 15% play-rate, move, there's a big chance they know the theory. Because of this, we play a move that's commonly played on the master level and avoids all the theory for Black. }
4. Nc3 { Avoiding complications that would arise after 4. cxd5. } 4... Bxf3
{ Objectively dubious, but Black thinks that it's at least a little more double-edged than   4...e6  cxd5  exd5  Bf4  Where White just has a very good position and is clearly superior. }
5. gxf3
{ I really like this move! We get to do our sacrifice on c4! Yay! :D  In fact, the engine is already saying White is much better and Black has no good options. If you look at the knights and pawns, this looks quite a lot like our normal 1... Nc6 positions, so you should be able to guess our next move! }
5... dxc4
{ Now we're even winning! This is the most common move, no questions asked, but   5...e6  cxd5  exd5  e4  was Black's best chance, though White is still much, much better. }
6. d5 { A very important move! Black probably underestimated or missed this. }
6... Ne5 { 6...Nb4??  You already know what to play, don't you?  Qa4+ } 7. f4
Ng6 8. Bh3
{ White is completely and utterly destroying Black in this position, due to our dominance on the light squares.  The engine is already saying +4 for White, so I think we can safely call it a day! It's also a very rare position, so if you want to know a bit more about what to do from here, I suggest you analyze a little deeper with the engine  (it shouldn't take long to fully understand how poor shape Black is in!) }
