[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5 - Réti Sicilian - 1... c5"]
[Black "Introduction to Chapter"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 c5
{ Welcome to the informational variation surrounding the move 1... c5, the 'Sicilian Invitation'.  This is the fourth most popular move for Black at the lower ratings. As explained in the informationalOpening Database, the move c5 is played roughly 10% of the time. Therefore, you can expect to see this position fairly often.  Black invites us to play the Sicilian  (hence the name, duh!)  with 2. e4, but we obviously stray away from this main line theory! }
2. c3
{ I really, really love this move! As someone who has played and deeply analyzed a lot 1. e4, 1. Nf3 and 1. Nc3, I know how difficult it can be to meet 1... c5. It's almost always impossible to play anything other than a main line Sicilian unless you're willing to sacrifice a good chunk of objectivity. Luckily, this is not the case with the Réti!  From here we will play for 3. d4 and NOT e4, allowing us to completely avoid Sicilian theory and instead play the opening on our terms from the get-go.  The position is somewhat reminiscent of the Alapin Sicilian, though we'd have a pawn on e4, and Black's main moves would be d5 and Nf6 to target this. In this position, we haven't committed a pawn to e4, so we have time to simply prepare for d4.  It's worth mentioning here, that   2...d6?  d4  cxd4  cxd4  is strictly worse than 2... d5 and Black's best move is to admit their mistake and spend an extra tempo on d5. }
