[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5 - Réti Sicilian - 1... c5"]
[Black "[1] 1 - Réti Sicilian - The Solid 2... Nc6 & 4... d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 c5 2. c3
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
2... Nc6
{ This is the most played move by Black, but most other moves can also transpose. }
3. d4
{ Following through with our plan, grabbing space in the center and preparing to recapture our d-pawn with our c-pawn. White already scores 56% from this point! }
3... cxd4 { The absolute main move by far, why else play c5? } 4. cxd4 d5
{ Black is keeping symmetry, but there are still some chances for us to outplay them. }
5. Bf4
{ We develop our bishop to its most logical square and take over the center. From here our plan is to play Nc3, e3 and Bd3. White already has a 58% winrate from this position, mostly due to it being much easier to play for us  (especially if you follow what I recommend in the course!) }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3
{ Just a nice developing move, not yet locking our bishop outside of our pawn-chain, as we can now still play Bd2 in case of Nh5. }
6... Bf5
{ Black is going for complete symmetry, but this allows us to put pressure on their position with a familiar move, maybe you can guess it? }
7. Qb3
{ If you found this, give yourself a big round of applause! We will play this in just about every position where Black plays Bf5 or Bg4. This is the whole reason why it's better for Black to play an early e6.  Black technically still has equal play here, but they have to find a hard-to-spot move, which they often fail to do.  Some common mistakes include:   7...e6?  This fails to address our idea  Qxb7  Now even the knight on c6 is under attack and White has a completely winning position.     7...b6?  This fails due to a nice move  e4!!  This is possible due to  dxe4  Bb5!  with d5 coming, White is completely winning and Black's position is falling apart. }
7... Qb6 { Keeping the symmetry? } 8. Qxb6
{ Breaking the symmetry! It should already be clear why 7... Qb6 wasn't optimal. }
8... axb6 9. a3
{ We stop ideas of both Nb4 and Bb4, while preparing to play moves like Rc1, Nb5, e3, Be2 and O-O.  White simply has a better position than Black, and with accurate play even a moderate advantage.   It's worth noting that   9...Nb4?!  Doesn't work due to  Rc1  Nc2+  Kd2!  With a winning position for White. }
