[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5 - Réti Sicilian - 1... c5"]
[Black "[6] 1 - Réti Sicilian - The Ambitious 2... d5 & 3... Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 c5 2. c3
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
2... d5
{ This seems to be the most testing move for Black, though it's also possible for this to transpose - and it often will. }
3. d4 Nc6
{ This move allows us to achieve a better position. It was necessary for Black to first play 3... e6, which we will look at in the next variation. }
4. dxc5
{ Our critical reply. Notice how we already have a pawn on c3?  That's gonna help us get to play b4! }
4... e5
{ The most played and ambitious move. Black is grabbing the entire center for a pawn and is very happy!  They shouldn't be, don't worry, I will show you ^^    4...a5?  This move falls flat due to White's killer response... Can you find it?  e4!!  What a blow! If Black doesn't capture, White captures the d5 pawn next move and is a clear pawn ahead  dxe4  Qxd8  Kxd8  Ng5!  Winning back the center pawn due to the fork, keeping the extra pawn }
5. b4
{ We're going to follow up with e3 and Bb2 with a clearly better position due to an extra pawn... What does Black have to show? }
5... a5
{ The thematic attack on the pawns! Just like we did in the previous chapter... right?    5...e4  Nd4  White is completely fine with nothing to worry about and an extra pawn }
6. b5
{ NOT the same as what we played! We were careful to never allow Black's pawns to advance like this, but in this variation, our pawns run loose and we end up with a clearly superior position. }
6... Na7
{ Funnily enough the mistake   6...e4?  bxc6  exf3  cxb7  Bxb7  exf3  Which leaves White two pawns up is played more than half the time. Even if Black gets a pawn back, White's position is still winning. }
7. Be3
{ I'm well aware of how crazy this position looks, so let me clarify a few things!  We're a pawn up, with our c5 pawn being protected and we're ready to capture on e5. If Black doesn't defend on e5, for example captures on b5, then we capture on e5. If Black DOES defend on e5, like f6, then we play a4 to support our b-pawn. If Black pushes with e4 we can meet it strongly with b6.  If we get to take the pawn on e5, our long-term plan is to play Bd4 and e3 with a better position and an extra pawn.  Phew! That is quite a mouthful. If you just spend a minute or two reading through the text a few times and looking at the position, it should be more and more clear, that Black has no compensation for the pawn and is just worse. }
