[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5 - Réti Sicilian - 1... c5"]
[Black "[7] 1 - Réti Sicilian - The Ambitious 2... d5 & 3... e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 c5 2. c3
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
2... d5
{ This seems to be the most testing move for Black, though it's also possible for this to transpose - and it often will. }
3. d4 e6
{ This is the most critical variation against our setup. Black realizes they shouldn't play the position like a Sicilian and instead transposes to a London. }
4. Bf4 { Developing in our usual fashion. } 4... Nc6 5. e3
{ We keep playing in a similar fashion, though it's no longer possible to play Nc3. We've already wandered off into territory that almost never arises through our move order.  I hope - and believe! - that our opponents aren't ready to play these positions, since they obviously invited us into a Sicilian with 1... c5. }
5... Nf6 6. Nbd2 Bd6 7. Bg3
{ This is a very equal position, where White might even claim a very slight advantage, though I believe it's more correct to assess it as drawish.  As always, we have ideas of Bd3, Rc1 and O-O, but in these specific positions, we can also look to play Bb5 and dxc5 - even Ne5 in true London spirit. It's worth noting, that if Black tries to challenge our bishop with Qc7, dxc5 just wins a pawn!  If Black goes for a more passive setup with O-O and b6, I would recommend going for the e4! break and therefore I generally prefer to play Bd3 as early as possible.  This position is very rare to reach through our move order and it looks nothing like a Sicilian, so I believe we still have good chances to outplay our opponents here! }
