[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6 - Réti Pirc 1... d6"]
[Black "Introduction to Chapter"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d6
{ The Pirc invitation!  Usually the Pirc is an opening that arises via. the move-order 1. e4 d6 and therefore most of the players will hope for us to play 2. e4, and some might even hope for 2. d4!  With this in mind, I decided to go for a different setup, that could only also arise from an English, where d6 just looks silly and Black usually doesn't understand what's going on. }
2. c4
{ This is the, in my opinion, easiest way to play against the Pirc invitation - by a landslide, even! - and it also gives great results in practice, with a 53% winrate and even higher in the main lines.  We give Black a position they probably aren't familiar with already on move 2 and provoke them to play the very natural-looking 2... e5, which will greatly limit how much we need to study and give us easy-to-play positions with objectively better chances.  We should always be happy to see 1... d6 on the board! Since the setup isn't very confrontational, there's a lot of different transpositions that can arise, which means we'll only look at the main tries.    2...Nf6  This will almost exclusively transpose into something we know either through  d4  g6  Transposing into the1... Nf6 chapter    2...Nf6  d4  Nbd7  This can transpose into both the Pirc  (this chapter)  and the aforementioned1... Nf6 chapter }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6 - Réti Pirc 1... d6"]
[Black "[1] 1 - Réti Pirc 1... d6 - The Quiet 3... Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d6 2. c4
{ For explanations, check the informational variation below.  Introduction to chapter }
2... e5
{ This is played around 45% of the time and also makes a lot of sense, since 1... d6 prepared for the e5 push.  Other moves like   2...Nf6  This is played around 15% of the time and either transposes to 1... Nf6/1... g6 territory or transposes to our text move after 3... e5   2...g6  This is played around 9% of the time and transposes to 1... Nf6/1... g6 territory }
3. Nc3
{ While it is possible to play 3. d4, we would like to wait a move to gain further control of the e4 square, which essentially means the e4 push  (for Black)  is impossible without them losing a pawn. This also makes a lot of sense in case of 2... Nf6, as 3. d4 would prevent 3... e5, but we want them to be able to transpose.  We're already doing slightly better and have a very comfortable position coming up, supported by a 57% winrate. }
3... Nf6
{ The most played move, with a playrate of around 33%, but not very good.  Black must, surely, have underestimated our next move.    3...Nc6  This doesn't really change anything and will almost exclusively transpose to one of the variations arising from 3... Nf6 }
4. d4
{ This is definitely the time to break in the center. We have enough control to make 4... e4 yet another inaccuracy  (which is played fairly often)  and other moves allow us to play e4 and, if Black captures on d4, get a strong knight in the center of the board. }
4... exd4
{ Releasing the tension straight over, played roughly 55% of the time. } 5.
Nxd4 Be7
{ Black is preparing to castle. It's also possible for them to play some other moves, but our general ideas will apply to just about everything Black can throw at us. }
6. e4 { We start by grabbing even more space. } 6... O-O 7. Be2
{ We're prepared to castle ourselves and all of our pieces are looking much better than our opponent's. }
7... c5
{ This is the most common way for Black to play for something, which could also be played earlier, since the e-pawn is already gone for Black and we have so much control over d5.  The main thing of concern for Black is now their weak d6 pawn. }
8. Nc2
{ The best square for the knight and a very thematic retreat!  We want to keep ideas of f4 and b3 open, while opening up our queen to eye down the backwards d6-pawn. }
8... Nc6 9. O-O
{ Black is already near busted with no active plan or counterplay. } 9... Ne5
{ The last try, played almost half of the time, but it simply falls flat. } 10.
f4
{ The pawn on c4 was already defended, so we just grab further space and control of the center.  We would usually play this move even without 9... Ne5 being played, though against a move like 9... Re8, f3 makes even more sense. }
10... Nc6 11. Bf3
{ We're the ones calling all of the shots and just about every single move is an idea for White, whether it's b3, h3, a4, Be3, Qe2 or Rad1.  Black's pieces are looking cramped and their pawns are weak, which combined leave White with a winning advantage.  We won't dive deeper, as this is already muuuch better for us and we're able to choose the setup that makes most sense for us  (what a privilege!^^) }
