3. Nc3
{ While it is possible to play 3. d4, we would like to wait a move to gain further control of the e4 square, which essentially means the e4 push  (for Black)  is impossible without them losing a pawn. This also makes a lot of sense in case of 2... Nf6, as 3. d4 would prevent 3... e5, but we want them to be able to transpose.  We're already doing slightly better and have a very comfortable position coming up, supported by a 57% winrate. }
3... Nf6
{ The most played move, with a playrate of around 33%, but not very good.  Black must, surely, have underestimated our next move.    3...Nc6  This doesn't really change anything and will almost exclusively transpose to one of the variations arising from 3... Nf6 }
4. d4
{ This is definitely the time to break in the center. We have enough control to make 4... e4 yet another inaccuracy  (which is played fairly often)  and other moves allow us to play e4 and, if Black captures on d4, get a strong knight in the center of the board. }
4... exd4
{ Releasing the tension straight over, played roughly 55% of the time. } 5.
Nxd4 Nc6
{ This position, perhaps, more often arises through the move order of 3... Nc6, 4... exd4 and 5... Nf6, but I've chosen to cover it through this move order. Like mentioned previously, there's a lot of possible transpositions, so we just want to keep our moves consistent and our plans thematic!  If Black had played 3... Nc6 instead of 3... Nf6 then 5... Nxd4 Qxd4 would transpose to the text move after Black develops their knight to f6. }
6. e4 { Very thematic push. } 6... Nxd4
{ This is the only unique way for Black to play, as Be7 would allow us to transpose with Be3, but now we didn't get allowed to play Be3. Don't worry, this is not a big deal! }
7. Qxd4 Be7
{ There's nothing better for Black than almost transposing.  The thematic   7...c5?!  Is no longer good for Black due to  Qd3!  with Bf4 and O-O-O coming next, White will win the d-pawn. }
8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O
{ Very thematic play, where the most popular move by a landslide is the mistake 9... c5?!, which we punish in the same way as 7... c5.  Because of this, we'll analyze a different approach from Black, so we can add some more thematic ideas! Always nice to have a full arsenal of weapons against the many options Black can play :D }
9... Be6
{ Not going for the thematic 9... c5  (which, yes, would be a mistake)   Quite a few Black players will even play 10... c5 after our next move, which STILL loses a pawn to Qd3, Bf4 and Rad1. }
10. f4 b6
{ This seems to be the most popular choice after 10... c5, as Black is now prepared to play d5! with the threat of Bc5! pinning our queen to our king! }
11. Kh1
{ Stepping out of harm's way with the king seems to be the simplest.  Now we've avoided all immediate danger and can look to play thematic moves like b3, Bb2, Be3, Bf3 and Rad1 with a significantly better position.   Black's bishops are looking very poor and their pawns are looking quite odd. It's not clear how they'll try to generate any counterplay. }
