6. Qb3
{ EDIT: Alright, I've seen a lot of missteps here from students who review this position, time for me to clarify my explanations! I have also decided to allow 6. e3, f3 and g3 as soft fails, even though they're not as strong as the text move, as they still leave White with a significant edge.  Whenever Black develops their light-squared bishop - especially if the knight is also still on b8, then Qb3 will be the objectively strongest move almost every single time.  It's important to not be too greedy about the b7 pawn, remember that Nc6 threatens to capture on d4! We're preparing to play e3 after Nc6 and only then look to capture on b7. Other than that, for example if Black defends the b-pawn, we're preparing to play g3 and Bg2 to win the pawn on e4.  Black has no good way of handling our threats and we therefore have a much better position, objectively we're already more than a full pawn ahead. }
