7. e3
{ We need to make room for our knight to move after it's gone back to g1.  It might seem like Black is getting all the space in the world, but notice how Black has NO pieces in play and a fairly vulnerable king in the center of the board. Because of this, I still like our chances. }
7... Nf6 { Black stops ideas of Qh5 and develops a kingside piece. } 8. Ng1
{ We're prepared to attack Black's kingside pawns with h4, make it awkward to develop the queenside with Qb3 and active our knight through Ne2-Ng3/Nf4.  White is objectively only slightly better, but Black has a very tight line to walk to avoid losing, very extended pawns and has a hard time developing.   Because of this, I would definitely place my bets on the White pieces. }
