{ While it is possible to play 3. d4, we would like to wait a move to gain further control of the e4 square, which essentially means the e4 push  (for Black)  is impossible without them losing a pawn. This also makes a lot of sense in case of 2... Nf6, as 3. d4 would prevent 3... e5, but we want them to be able to transpose.  We're already doing slightly better and have a very comfortable position coming up, supported by a 57% winrate. }
3... Be6
{ I must start by stating, that this move is quite a bad one. While it does technically attack our c-pawn, there's multiple ways for us to defend it, that all lead to a much better position. }
4. e3
{ I thought this to be the simplest and most thematic. We play like in the earlier chapters with c4, e3 and d4! A blast from the past, eh? }
4... Nf6 5. d4 { Time for the thematic push. } 5... exd4
{ 5...e4?  This even gives White a winning position after  Ng5  d5?  Qb3!  Where everything just collapses for Black. }
6. Nxd4
{ While it's also completely fine to take with the pawn, why not prepare to capture Black's bishop? }
6... Be7
{ Most people just let it happen, they want a stronger center, they believe their bishop was bad and they, understandably so, didn't want to move it yet again. }
7. Nxe6 fxe6 8. g3
{ With ideas of Bh3, Qb3, O-O and even Nd5! if Black plays Qd7 after Bh3, White has a much better - close to winning - position.  This is a little unorthodox, but basically, all of Black's pieces are awkward, our light-squared bishop and queen will wreak havoc on Black's weak light squares and the bishop pair and better pawn structure even means a better endgame. }
*

