[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7 - Réti Fianchetto - 1... g6"]
[Black "Introduction to Chapter"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 g6
{ This is fairly rare to see on the first move, but not to fear, it will very often transpose to a position that could arise through 1... Nf6.  The reasoning for this is simple, as Black you often want the knight to be on f6, and since most of the Black players idea behind the opening is to play e5 later, there's not really any other options for the Black knight.  This chapter will be dedicated only to variations that DON'T transpose into 1... Nf6, which will be a lot of them, which is also why this chapter doesn't have a lot of variations. }
2. c4
{ We want to play the exact same way and deploy the same setup as we do against 1... Nf6, in order to get as many transpositions as possible and keep our workload minimal. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7 - Réti Fianchetto - 1... g6"]
[Black "[1] 1 - Réti Fianchetto - The Early 5... e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 g6 2. c4
{ For explanations, check the informationalIntroduction to chapter } 2... Bg7
{ Why else play g6?   2...Nf6  This would obviously transpose to 1... Nf6, which happens just about every single time Black plays Nf6. This has a 25% playrate. }
3. d4
{ We follow in the same fashion as in the 1... Nf6 chapter. If you haven't already looked at that, go look at it before you continue with this chapter.  Our entire purpose in this chapter is to do everything possible to play thematic moves to transpose to 1... Nf6, as these positions were both good and it allows us to cut down on a lot of theory! }
3... d6
{ This is the most challenging setup from Black, as always. Black is preparing to break through later with either c5 or e5, just like in the 1... Nf6 chapter. }
4. g3 { Same as usual. } 4... Nd7
{ Preparing either c5 or e5 straight away, not spending time on Nf6. It's worth noting that   4...Nf6  Transposes to 1... Nf6 and is played more than 50% of the time! }
5. Bg2 e5
{ Black will keep playing without their knight on f6, but otherwise, they're playing in a similar fashion. }
6. dxe5 { We can simply get a good position by capturing. } 6... Nxe5 7. Nxe5
Bxe5
{ Notice how strong our light-squared bishop is now. It's hard for Black to complete development. }
8. O-O { No need to hurry. } 8... Ne7 { Preparing to castle short. } 9. Nc3
{ Developing our knight. } 9... O-O 10. Bh6
{ Threatening the rook. This didn't make sense on the move before due to Nf5. }
10... Bg7
{ This leaves White better, with many options and we can now trade our weak bishop for Black's strong bishop.    10...Re8  Bg5  This would be a better try for Black, though still better for White. }
11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. e4
{ Not the most critical try for us, but a very logical one, that also looks a lot like play in earlier variations.  Another try is   12.Qc2  Where White still has pressure on the b7 pawn and on the d6-pawn in case of c6, but Black can play 12... Nc6 and stay out of most of the trouble. }
12... Be6 13. b3
{ We simply have a  better position with moves like f4, Qd2/Qd3, Nd5, Re1 and Rad1 coming up.  Black's pieces are looking cramped and we have a titan grip on the center with tons of space. }
