[White "7 - Réti Fianchetto - 1... g6"]
[Black "[3] 1 - Réti Fianchetto - The Unique 4... Bg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 g6 2. c4
{ For explanations, check the informationalIntroduction to chapter } 2... Bg7
{ Why else play g6?   2...Nf6  This would obviously transpose to 1... Nf6, which happens just about every single time Black plays Nf6. This has a 25% playrate. }
3. d4
{ We follow in the same fashion as in the 1... Nf6 chapter. If you haven't already looked at that, go look at it before you continue with this chapter.  Our entire purpose in this chapter is to do everything possible to play thematic moves to transpose to 1... Nf6, as these positions were both good and it allows us to cut down on a lot of theory! }
3... d6
{ This is the most challenging setup from Black, as always. Black is preparing to break through later with either c5 or e5, just like in the 1... Nf6 chapter. }
4. g3 { Same as usual. } 4... Bg4
{ This isn't very critical, but is surely a way to attempt to create something without comitting a knight to f6. }
5. Bg2 c6
{ This setup with pawns on c6 and d6 is possible for Black in numerous other positions also, but it's often fairly dubious and rare to see.    5...Bxf3  Bxf3  This is also played a lot, but clearly White is completely fine. }
6. Nc3 Qb6
{ Though not the most played move, that would be 6... Bxf3, this is more testing. }
7. e3
{ EDIT: After having seen the many difficult moves in this position, I decided to add some more commentary.  Alright, so! Time for a new explanation! ^^  Black was threatening to play Bxf3 and take on d4 after, so we shouldn't play a move like 7. O-O or 7. e4, and Be3 hangs the pawn on b2 and blocks our e-pawn. }
7... Nd7 8. O-O Ngf6 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 O-O 11. a4
{ The last few moves have been extremely obvious and serve as a sample line to illustrate our point. We simply castle, play h3 to force Black to give up the bishop pair, play a4 to grab space and then play b3 to solidify our queenside pawns before moving our dark-squared bishop. White is substantially better here.  If Black doesn't play a5, we will, and else we'll look to play b3, Rb1, Ba3, Bg2, Qd3, Rd1 and perhaps even b4 and/or h4. Our position is very flexible and it's difficult to find any active plans for Black, as the e5 push is just ignored. }
