[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8 - Odds and Ends"]
[Black "Odds and ends - Owen's Defense - 1... b6"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 b6
{ This is a rare move played around 3% of the time, but it's still good to be prepared. }
2. e4
{ I looked at a few interesting setups, but ultimately decided on this, mostly due to it cutting down heavily on what Black can play and we have a novelty on move 6 against the main line to secure an advantage. }
2... Bb7 { Has to be played sooner or later. } 3. Nc3
{ Defending our pawn on e4. Generally speaking, what White wanted to achieve is e4, d4, Nc3, Bd3 and Qe2, but since we've already commited our knight to f3, we have to find our own setup against 1... b6 - Owen's Defense. }
3... e6
{ This is the only decent try and is played over half of the time.    3...g6?  d4  Bg7  Bd3  Concedes the entire center and is surely much better for White with h4 and Be3 coming next!     3...Nf6?!  This is not too bad, but not critical in the least  e5  Nd5  Nxd5  Bxd5  d4  e6  Bf4  Leaves White with a comfortable edge. }
4. d4
{ Seizing control of the center and preparing to develop the bishops.  Note how   4...Nf6  transposes to the variation mentioned on the previous move after  e5  Nd5  Nxd5  Bxd5  Bf4 }
4... Bb4
{ The only other try than 4... Nf6, also played almost 70% of the time. } 5.
Bd3
{ Since our knight is now pinned on c3, we add further defense to the e4 square.  White is already significantly better, but there's still one last variation we need to know. }
5... Nf6 { Adding further pressure on e4, how to respond? } 6. Nd2
{ This strong novelty has been played under 0,3% of the time in the position, but is the only move for a real White advantage!  The more common   6.Qe2?  Allows Black to equalize with  d5! }
6... Nc6
{ I really like our next move!    6...d5  e5  Ne4  Qg4!  Also nets White a moderate advantage! }
7. Ne2
{ If 6. Nd2 and 7. Ne2 isn't enough to surprise your opponent and secure a better position, then I honestly don't know what is!  We keep everything defended in the center and prepare to play either a3 and c3, completely cementing our center, and follow up with O-O and perhaps even c4 and Nf3. It's hard to see what Black can try to do now and we're just left with a much better position! }
