[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8 - Odds and Ends"]
[Black "Odds and Ends - The Dutch - 1... f5"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 f5
{ For some reason, the Dutch is only played slightly more than 1% of the time against 1. Nf3.  This left me scratching my head, as it's clearly a completely fine move and the best we can do is transpose to main line theory!  I decided to go for some fun line instead, to trick and outplay our opponent, but if you want to play principled   2.c4  Nf6  g3  Should net you a slight advantage after Bg2 and d4. }
2. e4
{ I decided to go for this forcing gambit! It's objectively decent and makes sure we don't have to learn too many variations and we get to avoid all Dutch theory, since this can ONLY arise through 1. Nf3 and 2. e4. }
2... fxe4
{ The only try for Black to not just allow White a much better position, due to Black's very vulnerable light squares. }
3. Ng5
{ An important move, preparing to recapture on e4.  While Black is currently a pawn up, the king is quite vulnerable on e8 and the light squares are open for grabs. We will look to fully utilize this. }
3... Nf6
{ The most obvious try, played roughly 75% of the time.    3...d5  doesn't change our plans much  d3  Nf6  (Very important move from Black, as h6 loses to Qh5+ and exd3 loses to Bxd3, reminiscent of the text move)  dxe4  h6  Again, an important move  Nf3  dxe4  Qxd8  Kxd8  Ne5  When all is said and done, and Black has flawlessly, which has never happened once, then the position is equal with White having full compensation for the pawn. }
4. d3
{ We want to tear open the light squares as soon as possible. Since we're threatening to capture back on e4 with a completely fine position, Black usually tries to keep the extra pawn.    4...d5  dxe4  Tranposes to the aforementioned variation on the previous move. }
4... exd3 { A common mistake, played almost 60% of the time. } 5. Bxd3
{ The light squares are too weak for Black to survive here. Our threat is to play Bxh7 and either Qh5+ to recapture on h7 or Bg6+ to save the bishop, with a much better position either way. }
5... g6
{ The only way to stop our ideas connected to capturing on h7, I decided to give it an exclamation mark, since almost all of our opponents will miss it and/or underestimate how important it is, even though we still are objectively much better after our next move. }
6. h4
{ We force the position open after h5 and will already look to gain a much better position after our attack. Our idea is to play 7. h5 and then either:  a. Capture on g6 with our h-pawn, if Black doesn't recapture our pawn  b. Play Bxh7, if Black captures on h5 with their pawn   c. Play Rxh5!! and Qxh5+!, if the knight captures on h5, with a completely won position.  White is much better already, borderline winning, which combined with how difficult it is to play for Black and how strong White's attack is both practically and objectively, I've decided to call it a decisive advantage.  Since these positions can ONLY arise through 1. Nf3, we should also be better prepared than our opponent, even though we only know this one variation  (and the mentioned subvariations throughout it)  , but if you wish to be even better prepared  (perhaps you know someone who plays the Dutch?)  then I urge you to analyze it a bit further yourself. }
