1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 b5 4. a4 Bd7
{ This move isn't actually covered in the theory section of the course, as it's not only a serious mistake for Black, it's also quite rare and allows White good play for multiple reasons. Can you figure out the simplest reason why?  Hint Black has decided to defend their b5-pawn with the light-squared bishop instead of the c-pawn, what difference does this make? }
5. axb5 Bxb5 6. Nc3
{ Great job! By luring the Black bishop onto b5 we now get to play Nc3 with tempo on the bishop and are even prepared to capture on c4 after the bishop moves.  The same ideas as always apply, 6... a6 leaves the bishop hanging and 6... c6 allows Nxb5 and b3. The engine is already saying around +2, meaning almost a decisive advantage for White. }
