1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 Nf6 4. Bxc4
{ The position so far is covered in the theory chapter below.  1 - The Conservative 3.. Nf6 }
4... Bg4
{ In this position Black usually plays the solid 4... e6, blunting our light-squared bishop, but here they instead developed their own light-squared bishop.  Can you punish Black and find the winning continuation?   It really is quite a pretty tactic, and a very common opening one at that! }
5. Bxf7+ Kxf7 6. Ne5+
{ If you found this yourself, very nicely done!  White will get back the piece after capturing the bishop with his knight and will simply be a pawn up in a position where Black can never castle and with a superior pawn-structure.  Because of the aforementioned reasons, this is a borderline decisive advantage.  It's good to note that   6...Kg8  Nxg4  Nxg4  Qb3+  This leads to forced mate, I thought this was important to share, as most people seem to simply recapture with the knight on g4, missing the checkmate! }
