[White "Puzzles"]
[Black "Puzzle #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 Nf6 3. cxd5 Nxd5 4. e4
{ Everything so far is covered in the variation below.  1 - Réti Gambit Declined - The Conservative 2.. Nf6 with 3.. Nxd5 }
4... Nf4
{ This is just a mistake from Black, as their knight doesn't make much sense on f4.  What's the best way to take advantage of this knight's poor placement? }
5. d4
{ A great double-edged move!  We both take over the center and open up our bishop, unleashing an attack on Black's knight, threatening to win a piece.  A possible continuation is   5...Ng6  Nc3  Where White simply has a far better center and many options for their pieces, meaning White has a significant advantage with many options. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Puzzles"]
[Black "Puzzle #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. d4 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nc3 Nbd7 7. O-O e5 8. e4
exd4 9. Nxd4 c5
{ How was it that we punished this mix of c5 and e5 by Black, mentioned multiple times in different variations throughout our 1... Nf6 chapter? }
10. Ndb5 { Exactly! The pawn on d6 will fall. } 10... Nb6
{ Black is threatening to take on c4, trying to spice things up. } 11. b3
{ Very well done! We have time to defend our pawn on c4 and now the pawn on d6 is hanging, leaving White with a decisive edge.    11.Nxd6  was also possible, but after  Bg4  Nxb7!  It's at the very least a bit messy, which we would like to avoid.  After revisiting this puzzle, I also realized Black has the very interesting, but difficult to spot   11...d5!?  which we meet with  12.e5!  Ng4  f4  dxc4  h3!?  With a rather wild, but very beneficial - borderline winning - position for White. }
