[White "Puzzles"]
[Black "Puzzle #16"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4 d5 3. c4 dxc4 4. d5 Nb8 5. e4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Bg4
{ This is just a mistake for Black that gives White a much better position.  Can you figure out why? }
7. Bxc4
{ Well done! A free pawn is a free pawn.  But can you also find the next blow? }
7... e6
{ Seems to be the only try for Black to not just be worse, but it doesn't work. }
8. Qb3
{ Very well done!  The queen comes out on b3 with a fork on the e6 and b7 pawns. This leaves White with such a much better position, that it's actually a decisive advantage.  It's also worth to know the following variation:   8...Qc8  Ng5  Where White is just even more-so winning, adding even further pressure on e6 and also x-raying the f7-pawn.  This tactic is also mentioned in the following variation2 - Mikenas Defense - The Simple 2... d5 with 3... dxc4 }
