{ This will be a model game showcasing one of our main lines of the Réti Gambit: Accepted 1... d5, 2... dxc4 & 3... Nf6. In this particular game, it started with 1. d4, but it transposed to our variation soon hereafter.  The game was a 10+0 rated game played in 2020 on lichess. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 e6 4. Bxc4 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Bxd2+ 6. Nxd2 Nf6 7. Ngf3 O-O
8. O-O Nc6 9. Rc1 Bd7 10. a3 a6 11. Qc2
{ This is explained in detail in the variation2 - The Conservative 3... Nf6, where we concluded a sizeable White advantage. Let's see how the game went on! }
11... Nd5 { Not the best move. What is the knight doing on d5? } 12. b4
{ The only poor move by White this game. White already had control over the b4 square and Black stops the potential b5 push, so there's no real reason behind the b4 push. }
12... Rb8
{ It almost feels wrong to give mistake or inaccuracy to this many moves in a row, but the moves just aren't accomplishing anything! }
13. Bd3 h6 14. Nb3
{ White has shuffled the bishop to a more sensible square and now is beginning the maneouvre of their knight into c5. I like this maneouvring by White! }
14... f5
{ This doesn't accomplish anything, other than weaken the e6 pawn.  Black has already pushed their h-pawn, so the White bishop couldn't capture on h7, so it's not necessary to also shut it down with f5.   Let's see how White punishes this! }
15. Nc5
{ Jumping in with the knight. Black's position is on the verge of collapse already. }
15... Be8
{ This was NOT IT! Black completely forgot that the f-pawn is no longer defending e6 and tries to deny White the opportunity to capture the bishop, but now it's just deadlost for Black. }
16. Nxe6 Qe7 17. Nxf8 Qxf8 18. Bc4
{ White is doing their best to keep the foot on the pedal and not give Black any breathing room. }
18... Bf7 19. Qxf5 Nde7 20. Bxf7+ Qxf7 21. Qxf7+ Kxf7
{ White has nothing to fear in this endgame. The position is still completely winning. }
22. Rc5 Rf8 23. Ne5+ { When ahead in material, exchanges favor you! } 23...
Nxe5 24. Rxe5 Nc6 25. Rf5+ Ke8 26. Rxf8+ Kxf8 27. Rc1
{ In this position, having had enough of this slaughter, Black chose to throw in the towel.  White is up an exchange and two pawns, so it's very understandable why Black resigned in this position. A great example of how to convert a winning advantage and how to exert pressure from the position we covered in our theory. }
