1. Nf3
{ This will be a model game showcasing one of our main lines of the Réti Gambit: Accepted 1... d5, 2... dxc4 & 3... Nf6. In this particular game, White played 2. d4, but it transposed to our variation soon hereafter.  The game was a 15+0 rated game played in 2018 on lichess. }
1... Nf6 2. d4 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. e3 dxc4 6. Bxc4 a6 7. e4 b5 8. Bd3 Bb7
9. a3 O-O 10. O-O
{ This is explained in detail in the variation3 - The Conservative 3... Nf6, where we concluded a sizeable White advantage. Let's see how the game went on! }
10... Nbd7 11. Qc2 g6 12. Bh6 Re8 13. h3
{ This was a completely unnecessary move, showing how White didn't realize what Black was threatening.  The move was clearly aimed at preventing Ng4, but the real threat was c5 by Black. }
13... Rc8
{ Giving White another chance to play the move, they should have played instead of h3. }
14. b4 { White finds the move, taking control over c5. } 14... Nb6 15. Qe2
{ Stopping Nc4. } 15... Nfd7 16. Bf4
{ A bit unnecessary, White should, yet again, have just played the move that succeeded this. }
16... Bd6 { Black keeps encouraging White to play the moves they're missing! }
17. e5 Bf8 { White is in complete control. } 18. Ne4 Be7 19. Rfc1 Nd5 20. Bd2
f6 21. Nc5
{ This was a bit unnecessary, but Black doesn't realize what White is threatening.    21.exf6  N5xf6  a4  This was even more promising for White. }
21... fxe5 { Completely missing White's threat! } 22. Nxb7
{ Not just winning the bishop, but also trapping the Black queen! There's no point in further commentary here. You can look at the rest of the moves, if you're interested in how White converted.  A common motive in these model games, is to just develop your pieces and get them to good squares, take control of the central breaks with your pawns and your opponent will almost always commit a horrific, game-losing mistake, to try and get some space back or counterplay. }
22... N7f6 23. Nxd8 Rcxd8 24. Nxe5 Nh5 25. Nc6 Rd6 26. Rc2 Bf6 27. Ne5 Nhf4 28.
Bxf4 Nxf4 29. Qf3 Nxd3 30. Nxd3 Bxd4 31. Rxc7 Rf8 32. Qg3 Be3 33. Qxe3 Rfd8 34.
Ne5 Rd5 35. Rac1 Rf8 36. Rc8 Rdd8 37. Rxd8 Rxd8 38. Rc7 Rd1+ 39. Kh2 Rd8 40.
Nd7 Re8 41. Nf6+ Kf8 42. Nxe8 Kxe8 43. Qxe6+ Kf8 44. Qf7# *

