{ This will be a model game showcasing one of our main lines of the Réti Gambit: Declined 1... d5, 2... d4 & 3... c5.  The game was a 5+0 rated game played in April 2021 on lichess in a below 2000 Blitz Arena. }
1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. e3 c5 4. b4 b6 5. bxc5 bxc5 6. Nxd4 cxd4 7. Qf3
{ This is explained in detail in the variation1 - The Ambitious 2... d4 with 3... c5, where we concluded a sizeable White advantage. Let's see how the game went on! }
7... Bd7
{ Black misses their chance to only give up a pawn, as covered in the aforementioned theory variation   7...dxe3  fxe3  Nc6  Qxc6+  Bd7  Where Black only lost a pawn, which compared to what happened in the game, is to be preferred. }
8. Qxa8 Bc6 { The queen is not trapped and the g2 pawn is defended. } 9. Qxa7
dxe3 10. Qxe3 e6 11. d4
{ Playing in the center and opening up for the pieces. } 11... Bb4+
{ It only eases White's task of converting with every trade. } 12. Bd2 Bxd2+
13. Nxd2 Nf6 14. d5 { A nice move! } 14... Bd7 15. Bd3
{ Preparing to castle, though even stronger would have been   15.Qc5!  Where Black now can't castle. }
15... O-O 16. dxe6 Bxe6 17. O-O Ng4 18. Qe4 Nf6 19. Qf3 Bg4 20. Qg3 Nc6 21. Ne4
{ White is getting their last pieces into play and preparing to trade even more. }
21... Bh5 22. a4
{ This move signifies the beginning of the marching pawns! Passed pawns must be pushed. }
22... Nb4 23. Bb1
{ Even stronger was   23.c5!  Calling out Black's bluff, as Black won't be able to capture on d3 due to White's threat of Nxf6+ followed by Qxd3 }
23... Qd4 24. Nxf6+ { Another trade. } 24... Qxf6 25. a5
{ A very nice move! White has seen that   25...Qxa1  Bxh7+!  Wins the Black queen, and with it, the game! }
25... Na6 { Blocking the pawn before it's too late. } 26. Ra3 Be2 27. Rc1
{ Getting the rook behind the other pawn, preparing to push that pawn also. }
27... Qb2 28. Qc3
{ Black has had enough at this point and decided to resign. White is completely dominating and all of Black's pieces are on awkward squares with no targets or threats. White has a harmonious position and can simply keep on pushing the pawns to eventually either get a queen or a ton of material.  A great example of how to convert an advantage from the position we covered in our theory. }
