[White "Model Games"]
[Black "bata1965 (1799) vs. ThinkingFastNSlow (1792)"]
[Result "*"]

{ This will be a model game showcasing one of our main lines of the Réti Gambit: Declined 1... d5, 2... d4 & 3... dxe3.  The game was a 5+0 rated game played in 2018 on lichess. }
1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. e3 dxe3 4. fxe3 Nf6 5. d4 Bg4 6. Be2 e6 7. Nc3 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. e4
{ This is explained in detail in the variation5 - The Ambitious 2... d4 with 3... dxe3, where we concluded a sizeable White advantage. Let's see how the game went on! }
9... c5
{ This seems like the most human response by Black, how else would they get any counterplay? }
10. d5
{ An important move, grabbing further space and cramping Black's pieces. }
10... exd5 11. cxd5 a6
{ This is a horrible blunder due to e5 and d6. Black had to play   11...Bd6  e5  Bxf3!  exf6  Bxe2  Qxe2  g6  In order to survive, though the position is still significantly better for White. }
12. e5 { Not hesitating to accept the space Black has given up. } 12... Nh5 13.
h3
{ Unnecessary. The direct   13.d6!  Was enough to obtain an easily winning position, where Black can safely wave the white flag. }
13... Ng3
{ This just doesn't work. White gets to capture all of Black's active pieces, gain some material and keep their colossal center with a winning position. }
14. hxg4 Nxf1 15. Bxf1 b5 16. d6 Bh4 17. Bf4 Nc6 18. g3 g5 19. gxh4 gxf4 20. g5
Kh8 21. Qd5 Qb6 22. Bd3
{ A horrendous blunder, that goes from more than +9 to under +3. This is still winning for White, but not nearly as convincing as   22.Qe4!  Clearing the d5 square for the knight, preparing the maneouvre of Nd5-Nf6, which was also played later on in the game. }
22... c4+
{ White's bishop is now hanging, but more importantly, Black gets to open up for their queen and White's king has gotten a little weak. }
23. Kg2 cxd3
{ I can't really fault Black for capturing a piece, especially after being deadlost, but some more precision was required   23...Nb4!  Was the last chance for Black to get the most out of the position, though White is still objectively winning. }
24. Qxd3 Rad8 25. Nd5
{ The idea is good, but it doesn't work! White needed to prepare for Nxe5 first. }
25... Qb7
{ Black missed their last chance for an almost equal game, and instead walking into a mate in two.   25...Nxe5!  Was required in this position.  Qe4  Qxd6  With only a slightly better position for White. }
26. Nf6 { Game. Over. } 26... Nxe5 { Sorry Black, you took the pawn too late! }
27. Qxh7#
{ Checkmate. While White did commit several blunders, the chances Black got were all quite difficult to spot and White was always in the lead from start to finish. While the execution of ideas wasn't flawless, it still does a great job at showing the overarching ideas and ways to play from the position we covered in our theory. }
