{ This will be a model game showcasing one of our sidelines of the Réti Gambit: Declined 1... d5, 2... c6 & 3... Bg4. In this game, Black played 2... Bg4 instead of 2... c6, but transposed on the next move.  The game was a 15+10 rated game played in 2020 on lichess. }
1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Bg4 3. c4 c6 4. Qb3 Qc7 5. Ne5 Qxe5 6. Qxb7
{ This is explained in detail in the variation4 - Réti Gambit Declined -  The Slav 2... c6 with 4... e6, where we concluded a winning advantage for White. Let's see how the game went on! }
6... Nf6 7. h3 Be6 8. d4 Qd6 9. c5
{ White is being surgical, grabbing as much space and control as possible, before finally capturing the rook on a8. }
9... Qd7 10. Qxa8 Qc7
{ Perhaps attempting to trap the queen with ideas of Bc8-Bb7, but the a7 pawn wouldn't be defended then, so there's no problem for White. }
11. Nc3 Bc8 12. b4
{ Grabbing further space on the queenside, preparing to bust the position open and use all the pieces to overwhelm Black. }
12... Nfd7 13. b5 e6 14. bxc6 Nxc6 15. Rb1 Be7 16. Nb5 Qa5+ 17. Bd2
{ Black is now also losing the knight on c6. The game is just completely over. A great example of how White can completely steamroll Black with simple play, grabbing control of the center and activating their pieces.  White is already +11 and didn't make a single inaccuracy for the rest of the game either, not giving any breathing room to Black. }
17... Qd8 18. Qxc6 O-O 19. Nxa7 Nf6 20. Rb8 Bd7 21. Rxd8 Bxc6 22. Rxf8+ Bxf8
23. Nxc6 Ne4 24. Bb4 g5 25. a4 f5 26. Ba6 f4 27. Bc8 Kf7 28. exf4 gxf4 29. Nd8+
Ke7 30. Nxe6
{ Having had enough of the slaughter, Black resigned in this position. } *

