{ This will be a model game showcasing one of our sidelines of the Réti Gambit: Declined 1... d5, 2... Nf6 & 3... Nxd5. In this particular game, it started with 1. d4, but it transposed to our variation soon hereafter.  The game was a 5+0 rated game played this month  (July 2021)  on lichess. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nf6 3. cxd5 Nxd5 4. e4 Nb6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. Be2 e6 7. Be3 Bb4+ 8.
Nc3 O-O 9. O-O
{ This is explained in detail in the variation1 - The Conservative 2... Nf6 with 3... Nxd5, where we concluded a comfortable White advantage. Let's see how the game went on! }
9... f5
{ Lashing out, as leaves the e6 pawn very weak to moves like Ng5 and Qb3. } 10.
Ne5
{ One of the few times a central square is bad for a knight.  It looks pretty on e5, but is hitting close to nothing. }
10... N8d7 { What!? Black must have missed White's next move. } 11. Nxg4 fxg4
12. Bxg4
{ White has a very real advantage now, a game-winning one, even, as White has won the bishop pair, a pawn and the pawn on e6 is extremely weak. }
12... Nf6 13. Bxe6+ Kh8 14. Qb3 a5 15. a3
{ A bit unnecessary, but fine nonetheless. Made more sense to play in center with moves like 15. e5 or 15. f3. }
15... Be7
{ The bishop is not worth preserving, especially not on such a bad square, and there's ways for White's knight to jump into the game and be influential. }
16. Rad1 Nbd7 17. e5 Nh5 18. Nd5
{ All of White's pieces are getting into the game, so now it's just about finishing the job. }
18... Bg5 19. Bxg5 Qxg5 20. Bxd7 { Winning a piece. } 20... c6 21. Ne3 a4 22.
Qe6 Nf4 23. Qg4 Qh6 24. Nf5
{ It was at this moment, that Black decided it was over. There's nothing better than to either give up the rook for the knight or allow the queen trade, both leading to a simply completely lost endgame.  This was a great game to illustrate how White can gain a winning position by playing in the center and activating the pieces. }
