[Result "*"]

{ This will be a model game showcasing one of our main line of the Réti Mirrored 2... g6 The Slow 6... Nbd7 with 7... e5. In this particular game, it started with 1. d4, but it transposed to our variation soon hereafter.  The game was a 3+2 rated game played in 2018 on lichess. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 d6 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O Nbd7 7. Nc3 e5 8. e4
exd4 9. Nxd4 Ne5 10. b3 Bg4 11. f3
{ This is explained in detail in the variation1 - Réti Mirrored -  2... g6 The Slow 6... Nbd7 with 7... e5, where we concluded a moderate White advantage. Let's see how the game went on! }
11... Bd7 { The most common retreat. } 12. Be3 Qe7 13. Qd2 c5 14. Ndb5
{ White has just been playing thematic moves that we've mentioned and clearly already has a much better position with very active pieces. }
14... a6 15. Qxd6
{ While this is still much better for White and prepares to trade into a better endgame   15.Nxd6  with ideas of Bxc5 and f4, would be even better. }
15... Qe8 16. Nc7 { Black is now completely lost. } 16... Qb8
{ Trying to pin the queen on d6. } 17. Qxe5 { Just capturing the free piece. }
17... Re8 18. Qxc5 { Capturing a pawn and keeping the knight defended. } 18...
Rc8 19. Bf4
{ Adding further protection to the knight. We can already stop the commentary at this point, as White is a piece and two pawns up. }
19... Nxe4 20. Nxe4 Bxa1 21. Rxa1 Ra7
{ I just wanted to quickly mention, that funnily enough this allows mate in 7 after   22.Qd4  Qxc7  Nf6+  Kg7  Ne8+  Kf8  Qh8+  Ke7  Bg5+  f6  Qxf6+  Kxe8  Qe7# }
22. Qa5 b6 23. Nxa6 bxa5 24. Nxb8 g5 25. Nxd7 Rxd7 26. Bd6 Rcd8 27. c5 f5 28.
Nxg5 Rxd6 29. cxd6 Rxd6 30. f4 Rd2 31. a4 Rb2 32. Rc1
{ It was at this moment, that Black decided it was over. There's a potential fork on d5, so Rxb3 isn't an option, and there's no more tricks for Black to even try.  This was a great game to illustrate how White can gain a winning position by playing in the center and activating the pieces. }
