[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "throndk (1750) vs. Nikitosik2008 (1647)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This will be a model game showcasing one of our main line of the Mikenas - The Simple 2... d5 with 3... dxc4. In this particular game, it started with 1. d4, but it transposed to our variation soon hereafter.  The game was a 15+10 rated game played in 2020 on lichess. }
1... d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d5 Nb8 5. e4 e6 6. Bxc4 exd5 7. Bxd5 Nf6 8.
Bxf7+ Ke7 9. Qb3
{ This is explained in detail in the variation1 - Mikenas Defense - The Simple 2... d5 with 3... dxc4, where we concluded White was completely winning. Let's see how quickly Black crumbled! }
9... Nc6 { Trying to at least get the knight out. } 10. Bd5
{ A very respectable move, just getting the bishop out of harm's way, preparing to castle and take complete control over the center. }
10... Nxd5
{ While this is objectively probably the best move, it still doesn't work  (since White is completely winning)  . The position will open up completely around the Black king and the knight won't have a good home. }
11. exd5
{ Black is in huge trouble. Moving the knight back would allow White to win the queen, moving the knight to a5 or e5 would allow White to capture the knight. }
11... Ne5
{ Black crumbled and played the knight to its least attractive square.   11...Na5  Qa3+  Kf7  Qxa5  At least saves the queen from the skewer and lets the king sort-of escape, though Black is obviously still completely lost and a piece down. }
12. Nxe5
{ A piece down and with Bg5+ still being a threat, the engine saying +9 for White, Black decided they had enough and threw in the towel. It took White 3 moves to win from our covered position!  That's gotta be some sort of record in efficiency! :D }
