[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Student Games"]
[Black "Tempranilloblack (1171) vs. Stormbornboy (1178)"]
[Result "*"]

{ This will be a model game showcasing our main line of Réti Gambit: Accepted 1... d5 & 2... dxc4.  The game was a 5+5 rated Blitz game played on chess.com. }
1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 b5 4. a4 c6 5. axb5 cxb5 6. Nc3 b4 7. Qa4+
{ A good move, not moving the knight from c3, but instead forking the pawn on b4 and Black's king!  All the moves so far have been explained in detail in the variation1 - The Overambitious 3... b5, where this exact move was mentioned in a clickable.   White already has an objectively winning position, so let's see how tempranillo went about punishing Black for their play! :P }
7... Bd7 8. Qxb4 e6 9. Qxc4
{ Moving the queen away from the attack of Black's dark-squared bishop and grab a second pawn... What more can you want!? }
9... Nf6 10. d4 { Why not grab the center? } 10... Bd6
{ Ouch, this move really doesn't work due to a nice response for White. } 11.
b3
{ Oh no! White didn't spot the refutation to Black's move, namely:  11.e4!  with the threat of forking with e5  11...Be7  12.e5  Nd5  13.Nxd5  exd5  14.Qxd5  certainly looks very good with the entire center under our control and yet another pawn won!   I've observed that quite a few students have a tendency to play b3 and often fail to play e4 in middlegames where their opponent walk into it  (like here)  , so be on the lookout for these tendencies in your own games! }
11... O-O 12. Ba3
{ The point behind White's move is revealed. Simply trade off Black's strong bishop, which makes sense, but we obviously saw how that bishop wouldn't have even been strong with perfect play, though it's too much to ask for us mere mortals to spot all of these perfect moves! :P }
12... Qa5 13. b4
{ I like this move! The pin along the a-file was pretty awkward, so we look to break it with tempo on Black's queen with ideas of b5 even being possible now. }
13... Qa6
{ Uh-oh! Black was too focused on keeping their pin along the a-file and now walks straight into trouble! }
14. Qxa6 Nxa6 15. Bxa6
{ It was in this position that Black decided to throw in the towel and resign with White currently being a knight and a pawn up.  This was a great game to illustrate the kinds of middlegames that are likely to arise from some of the sidelines Black can throw at you, and how you can handle these with thematic play and earn some sweet rating with quick, fun games!  Thank you for your game submission tempranillo and congratulations on getting this game picked for the chapter! :D }
