[White "Student Games"]
[Black "lettucecheckmate (1225) vs. Florid50 (1189)"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ This will be a model game showcasing our main line of Réti Gambit: Accepted 1... d5 & 2... dxc4.  The game was a 15+10 rated Rapid game played on chess.com. }
1... d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 b5 4. a4 c6 5. axb5 cxb5 6. Nc3 Bd7 7. Ne5 e6 8. Qf3
{ All the moves so far have been explained in detail in the variation1 - The Overambitious 3... b5, where we concluded a decisive advantage for White in this position. }
8... Na6
{ Oh no... Black moves the knight to defend the rook on a8, they don't put a piece on c6, so they avoid losing a piece! Unfortunately, they missed our other threat. }
9. Qxf7#
{ Checkmate!  I know that this model game technically is only a single move apart from theory, but I still wanted to cover it because I feel like 8... Na6 is a "logical" response from Black, defending from all other threats than Qxf7#, and I also think it's nice to see just how many quick wins people get from our absolute main line of the course!  Hopefully you're excited to play equally sweet games yourself :P  Thank you for your game submission Lettucecheckmate and congratulations on getting this game picked for the chapter! :D }
