[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Student Games"]
[Black "Bechster (1900) vs. R-Parsa (1984)"]
[Result "*"]

{ This will be a model game showcasing a rare sideline of Réti Mirrored: 1... Nf6 & 2... c6  The game was a 3+2 rated Blitz game played on lichess. }
1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c6
{ A very interesting and weird way of playing... is this some kind of Slav or Caro-Kann? }
3. d4 d5 4. e3
{ We've actually transposed to the Slav, but this is still a completely fine position to play and an unsuspecting Black player still has to be very careful. }
4... Bg4 5. Qb3 { Thematic moves! } 5... Qb6 6. Ne5 Qxb3 7. axb3 e6 8. Nxg4
Nxg4
{ White already has a sizeable lead after  9.c5!  - or even  9.Bd2!?  -  to limit Black's dark-squared bishop and prepare for b4-b5 ideas. }
9. h3 { A logical move, but now Black has time for  9...Bb4+! } 9... Nf6
{ Allowing c5 again. } 10. Nc3 { Allowing Bb4 agian. } 10... Bd6
{ Okay, now Black is just asking for c5 to come! } 11. c5
{ c5 finally comes and now White has a great position! } 11... Bc7 12. b4
{ The b-pawn starts rolling. } 12... Nbd7
{ This allows the pawn to keep going with great strength. } 13. b5
{ Using that doubled b-pawn to perfection, you love to see it! } 13... Bd8
{ What is this!? Black feared b6 so much that they played Bd8... I have no words other than White is now totally winning! }
14. bxc6 bxc6 15. b4
{ Getting the other b-pawn into play, this is just looking too easy. } 15...
O-O 16. b5 cxb5 17. Bxb5 e5 18. Bc6 Rc8 19. Bxd5
{ It's hard for me to give this a blunder, as it's extremely logical and White is still better, but it does allow Black to avoid being lost with some crazy tactical ideas connected to 19... exd4 and 20... Nxc5!   19.Bxd7!  Nxd7  20.Nxd5  was the way to go. }
19... exd4 20. exd4 Re8+ 21. Be3 Nxd5
{ Black fails to find the crazy  21...Nxc5!  that we talked about and is now completely lost again. }
22. Nxd5 Nf6 23. Nxf6+ Bxf6
{ Even though Black is only down a pawn currently, the a7 pawn is in serious trouble and White's two pawns are connected passed pawns, so now it's just a matter of technique, but a more interesting matter of technique than it normally is! }
24. O-O Re7 25. Ra6
{ Getting the rook to a6 to both prepare c6 and threaten the a8 pawn. Great logical multi-purpose move. }
25... Re4 26. Rd1
{ Taking the time to defend the pawn on d4 instead of being hasty and capturing on a7. }
26... Bh4 { Just a pointless pass for Black. } 27. Rxa7
{ Ideas of c6 and d5 were probably faster, but who can judge a man for grabbing an extra pawn first!? }
27... h6 28. d5 { Now the march begins. } 28... Bg5 29. Bxg5 hxg5 30. c6 Kf8
31. d6 { Keep pushing those pawns! } 31... Re6 32. d7 { Keep 'em going! } 32...
Rd8 33. c7 { Don't stop! } 33... Rxd7 34. c8=Q+ Re8 35. Qxd7
{ It was in this position that Black lost on time  (with 12 seconds on the clock)  , so I will assume that they decided to 'resign' by leaving the game.  This was a great example of how to use thematic ideas to meet logical tries that aren't covered explicitly in the course and how to snowball a lead in the middlegame to a winning endgame.  Thank you for the game submission Bechster and congratulations on getting this game picked for the chapter! :D }
