[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Student Games"]
[Black "Kouga16 (1601) vs. isuckatchessbutilwin (1561)"]
[Result "*"]

{ This will be a model game showcasing a rare sideline of Réti Mikenas Defense: 1... Nc6 & 2... Nf6.  The game was a 3+2 rated Blitz game played on lichess. }
1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4 Nf6 { Already we leave known theory. What is this move!? } 3.
c4
{ We already have a comfortable lead in development, just look at our pawns! }
3... e6 4. e3 { Simple does it. } 4... Ne4
{ This doesn't make a lot of sense, as the knight on e4 is more of a target than a strength. }
5. Nbd2 { A little passive, but still completely fine. } 5... Bb4 6. a3
{ Getting the bishop pair. } 6... Bxd2+ 7. Bxd2
{ While it's certainly tempting to recapture with the bishop and get it into play, the bishop is still not activated on d2, and now we're justifying Black's knight on e4.   As of such, it would have been better to play the unthematic  7.Nxd2! }
7... O-O 8. Bd3 { More logical development. } 8... f5 9. O-O b6 10. d5
{ Striking in the center! I like it. } 10... exd5 11. cxd5 Ne7 12. Bb4
{ The pieces are getting activated, and now Black no longer can capture the bishop on d2. }
12... c5
{ Uh-oh, this ambitious move doesn't work at all, and White just has a winning sequence now. }
13. dxc6
{ Black is in huge trouble here, which White will beautifully illustrate. }
13... dxc6 14. Bc4+
{ The good moves keep coming!  Now Black has to part ways with either the exchange with the move that they chose or the knight with Qxd8 and Bxe7. }
14... Nd5 15. Bxf8 Qxf8 16. Bxd5+ cxd5 17. Qxd5+
{ Ouch! Now the rook is also hanging on a8. } 17... Be6
{ Giving up the bishop instead of the knight. } 18. Qxe6+
{ Okay, now White is just up a rook and a pawn with a completely winning position and we can call it a day here in terms of analysis.  The rest is just a matter of technique ^^ }
18... Kh8 19. Rac1 Re8 20. Qd7 Re7 21. Rc8 Rxd7 22. Rxf8#
{ That is mate on the board! A great illustration of how to apply thematic ideas in unorthodox positions and get a very comfortable edge out of the opening to nurture into a won position later and drive the full point home.  As I've pointed out a few times already, it is so vital to have the ability to find your own moves and plans against these offbeat tries by your opponents, as they will happen, and there are way too many to cover!   Hopefully this game has inspired you and a thank you goes out to Kouga16 for the game submission and congratulations on getting this game picked for the chapter! :D }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Student Games"]
[Black "Kouga16 (1793) vs. Vossi_20 (1936)"]
[Result "*"]

{ This will be a model game showcasing our main line of Réti Pirc: 1... d6 & 2... d4.  The game was a 5+5 rated Blitz game played on lichess. }
1. Nf3 d6 2. c4 e5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 e4 5. Nd2 Bf5 6. Qb3
{ All the moves so far have been explained in detail in the variation4 - Réti Pirc 1... d6 - The Quiet 3... Nf6, where we concluded that we had a much better position, and that we're objectively speaking  already more than a full pawn ahead.  Let's see how White uses this in the game, shall we? }
6... Nc6 7. e3
{ An important finesse, not rushing to capture on b7, but instead recognizing that the pawn on d4 is under attack  (as also explained in the text of the aforementioned variation) }
7... Rb8 8. Qb5
{ Here it would have been wiser to play for  8.Qc2!  and look to capture the  e4  pawn, as Black has no way of defending it. Anyhow, let's see how this goes! }
8... Qd7
{ The only good move and perhaps what White had missed/underestimated. The bishop doesn't have to move from f5 and now the Black queen is also activated. }
9. d5
{ Forcing Black to find the continuation of  9...Ne5!  10.Qxd7  and  10...Kxd7!  to equalize, where Black's pieces will still look a little odd. }
9... a6
{ Black crumbles under the pressure and allows White a devastating blow. This is very common when we apply pressure to Black's position, as they feel uncomfortable due to not knowing the position at all, and will end up playing a horrendous move! }
10. dxc6 { Now the threat is to capture on d7 with check. The game is over. }
10... Qxc6 { This is even worse than capturing on b5. } 11. Qxf5
{ Ouch, suddenly White is up two pieces and the pawn on e4 is still hanging. }
11... Be7 12. Ndxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Qd7 14. Nd5
{ White will even trade on e7 now. Black chose to throw in the towel and resign.  This was a great illustration of how even if you don't find the most objectively critical moves, if you simply put pressure on your opponent's position, you can make the crack very quickly and get a quick, nice win.  Thank you for your game submission Kouga16 and congratulations on  (also!)  getting this game picked for the chapter! :D }
