[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Student Games"]
[Black "QuantumJoe (2110) vs. Ashwanth_Subramanian (2177)"]
[Result "*"]

{ This will be a model game showcasing our main line of Réti Gambit: Declined 1... d5 & 2... d4.  The game was a 3+0 rated Blitz game played on lichess. }
1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. e3 c5 4. b4
{ All the moves so far have been explained in detail in the variation1 - The Ambitious 2... d4 with 3... c5, though it deviates so early that it's technically also covered in jsut about every other variation as well.  Black will deviate from our theory on the next move. }
4... e5
{ This isn't a very good move, but somewhat surprisingly, not that bad either. }
5. Nxe5
{ It's obviously best to capture the pawn, but now our knight is somewhat misplaced and Black can try to activate their pieces rapidly to compensate for the pawn, though they won't get full compensation. }
5... cxb4 { This is a thematic way of playing for Black. } 6. a3 dxe3 7. fxe3
{ This is starting to almost look like something we know! } 7... Nc6 8. Nxc6
bxc6 9. d4 c5
{ This is just a blunder. Black had to try  9...Qh4+!?  10.g3  Qe4!  with decent chances. But here White just gets the entire center and already has a winning position. }
10. axb4
{ Getting Black's c-pawn away from the center and getting full control over it. }
10... cxb4 11. Bd3
{ While the engine really likes playing c5 earlier, I think this is a more human move to play, and White also ended up being rewarded for their patience. }
11... Bb7
{ Encouraging White to castle, which they would have done anyhow. What's the point? }
12. O-O Bd6 { Now Black is just begging for c5 to come! } 13. c5 Qg5
{ Black most likely knows that they're doomed and is just trying to go for brute-force attacks with mate in mind. White shuts it down brilliantly. }
14. e4 { Why not stop the mate by getting further control over the center? }
14... Bxh2+ 15. Kxh2 { Just calling Black's bluff. } 15... Qh4+ 16. Kg1 O-O-O
17. Rxa7
{ No fear! The Black king is the one who's in trouble, not the White one! }
17... Rxd4 18. Be3
{ One of the only inaccurate moves in this brilliant game, but you can't really blame someone for playing a natural +13 move instead of a +21, can you? }
18... Rd7 19. Qf3
{ Again, not the fastest, with  19.Rxb7!  being mate in 10 with correct play, but obviously difficult to calculate, so this is very logical as well! }
19... Nf6 20. Bb5 Re7 21. c6 Rxe4 22. cxb7+ Kc7 23. Nd2 Rg4 24. Qc6+ Kd8 25.
b8=Q#
{ A very nice, and overwhelming, mate with 2 queens, 2 rooks and 2 bishops on the board!  This was a great game to show how to apply thematic ideas outside of the theoretical variations and how to punish our opponent for their mistakes with strong center play and ambitious piece play.  Thank you for your game submission QuantumJoe and congratulations on getting this game picked for the chapter! :D }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Student Games"]
[Black "Antilokus (2004) vs. Braulino (1913)"]
[Result "*"]

{ This will be a model game showcasing something completely outside of our normal theory! It is also important to have the ability to use the ideas and themes shown throughout the chapters to find your own way of playing once things step outside of the covered variations.  The game was a 5+3 rated Blitz game played on lichess. }
1. Nf3 c5 2. c3 { So far, so good. } 2... g6
{ What is this!? Black allows us to play for d4 and e4 and grab the center. }
3. d4 { Remember to say 'thank you' when your opponent is this kind! } 3... Bg7
{ Black really doesn't want anything to do with the center, but this will surely cost them. }
4. e4
{ No need to hesitate! Black isn't developing their pieces and isn't challenging our center, so we can go right ahead with this move as well.  Look at our fantastic center play already. Black has to be very precise to not get steamrolled. }
4... cxd4 { Good move, why else would there be a pawn on c5? } 5. cxd4 Qa5+
{ I'm sorry, but what is this absolute nonsense!?  Black is checking our king and encouraging us to develop a piece for free, while also misplacing their queen on a5. This doesn't play for the center, doesn't active pieces, and doesn't win any material.  Believe it or not, but White is actually already winning here! There's also still 1000 games in the database  (at the 1600 level)  with this position, which is completely shocking to me... how has so many players played like this!? }
6. Nc3 Nc6 7. Be2
{ Just logical development, no need to be fancy or try to find a knockout blow. }
7... Qb4
{ This hopes to win either the b2 or d4 pawn, but doesn't work at all. } 8. a3
{ The simplest move, though   8.Be3!?  actually works due to  8...Qxb2  9.Nb5!  where Black is toast. But okay! No need to complicate the position. }
8... Qd6 9. Be3
{ Only now developing the bishop and defending the d4 pawn.  Look at those harmonious pieces and center pawns! }
9... e5
{ Black lashes out and tries to pressure the d4 pawn, but it doesn't work at all.  FUN FACT: the engine is saying +9 for White now, but even before this move, it was saying +5! That's how important playing for the center and developing your pieces is. }
10. d5 { Here comes the d-pawn! } 10... Nce7 11. Nb5
{ And the knight! Black is beginning to feel the fury of White's fully developed army. }
11... Qb8 12. Rc1
{ Even the rook is joining the fight!  Black has spent 4 moves on their queen, while White has just gotten all of their pieces into the game. It's clear to see the difference when you look at the board. }
12... Kf8 { Just trying to dodge Nc7+. } 13. Nc7
{ The knight comes in anyway and wins the rook!  While it might be slightly better to keep developing pieces and attacking instead of grabbing material, I think it's a great practical decision to grab a little material before continuing with the onslaught. }
13... Bh6 14. Nxa8 Qxa8 15. Qd2 Bxe3 16. Qxe3 Kg7 17. Nxe5
{ Okay, now White has won an exchange and a pawn, while still having much better pieces, so we can stop the commentary here.  The engine is saying almost +9 here and it's clear that Black is toast. }
17... Nf6 18. f3 Re8 19. Nc4 Nexd5 20. Qd2 Nb6 21. Nd6 Re6 22. O-O Qb8 23. Nxc8
Nxc8 24. Rfd1 Re5 25. Qd4 Rh5 26. g3 Ne7 27. f4 Nc6 28. Qe3 Rh6 29. e5 Nh5 30.
Rxd7 Qc8 31. Rcd1 Qe8 32. Bxh5 Rxh5 33. Qc3 Qe6 34. Kg2 Qh3+ 35. Kf3 Rh6 36.
e6+ Kf8 37. Rxf7+ Ke8 38. Qh8#
{ A great game and display of how to use the opening principles and some of the ideas shown in the course to completely destroy your opponent when they attempt to sidestep theory and play a 'unique' opening setup instead.  Thank you for your game submission Antilokus and congratulations on also  (third time!)  getting this game picked for the chapter! :D }
