[Black "Antilokus (2028) vs. serpitirimov (2132)"]
[Result "*"]

{ This will be a model game showcasing our main line of Réti Gambit: Declined 1... d5 & 2... d4.  The game was a 5+3 rated Blitz game played on lichess. }
1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 d4 3. e3 c5 4. b4 b6 5. bxc5 bxc5 6. Nxd4 cxd4 7. Qf3
{ All the moves so far have been explained in detail in the variation1 - The Ambitious 2... d4 with 3... c5.  Black will deviate from our theory on the next move. }
7... Qb6
{ Black is trying to trap White's queen after we capture on a8, but this doesn't work at all. }
8. Qxa8 { Calling out the bluff. } 8... Nf6
{ Blacks is preparing to play Nfd7 and Bb7 to trap our queen, following through with their plan. }
9. exd4
{ This is certainly still winning, as Black can't capture on d4 due to Qxb8 and we prepare ideas of c5 to finally get our queen out.   It would have been more precise to play  9.Na3!  to prepare Rb1 and stop all ideas of trapping our queen and even look to capture on b8 or play Nb5. }
9... Nfd7
{ Black keeps going with their plan, but here White finds a nice resource. }
10. c5
{ A great way to not just get the queen out, but also preparing to attack! }
10... Qb4 11. c6
{ It was in this position Black decided they had suffered enough and threw in the towel.  Bb7 doesn't work here due to cxd7, so already Black has to abandon their original plan of trapping the queen, and if that plan doesn't come to fruition, then there's obviously no counterplay.  Not only that, but White is also threatening to play c7! now and either win the knight on b8 or bishop on c8. The engine is already saying +9, which I even think might be an understatement in practical terms, so it definitely wasn't an early resignation.  A great game to illustrate how to stay calm after grabbing the rook on a8 and find comfortable ways to eliminate counterplay and drive the full point home!  Thank you for your game submission Antilokus and congratulations on also getting this game picked for the chapter! :D }
